<HEAD>Senate Negotiators Agree To $9.4 Billion War On Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-5 pvs bgng: ``Republicans said,'' with new grafs
3-5 bgng: ``As part,'' to update with drug package nailed down, passage
of two appropriations bills. Should stand for AMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senator negotiators agreed Tuesday to boost the war on drugs to $ 9.4 billion, capping a week of talks with the White House and lifting a Republican blockade that stalled action on four money bills. `` It seems that everything is worked out so we have an agreed-upon package,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, the chief <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> As part of their deal, <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> agreed that later this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would consider elements of a crime-fighting package unveiled by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in June but dormant since then. With the agreement in hand, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed two of four appropriations bills that had been stalled by Republicans for more than a week in a move to gain leverage in bargaining over the drug package. Within an hour the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a $ 14.4 billion foreign aid measure and a $ 157.4 billion bill for labor, health and education programs. The White House indicated its approval of the agreement earlier in the day before it was cemented. Presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the outlines of the plan appeared `` consistent with our objectives.'' `` We do expect to accept this arrangement and hopefully we can get on with implementing the drug plan,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The negotiations began early last week after Democrats proposed to add $ 2.2 billion to the $ 7.9 billion proposed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in his Sept. 5 address to the nation on the scourge of drugs. They said that education, treatment and prevention programs were underfunded in the administration's battle plan for fighting the drug war. The freshly minted package funds the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's initial $ 7.9 billion war on drugs plus $ 400 million in other crime-fighting money requested by the president in June as well as $ 200 million for juvenile justice programs and the $ 900 million boost that had been the center of week-long negotiations The $ 900 million would provide $ 100 million for law enforcement and the rest for prevention, education and treatment, the `` demand side'' of the drug war that Democrats say was underfunded in the president's original plan. `` Without building up the demand side, then we're really caught fighting the drug war with one hand behind us,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. Actually, the $ 200 million for juvenile justice already was contained in a bill to provide money for the State, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Departments </ORGANIZATION>. Moving them into the drug package, raised the total added by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to $ 1.1 billion, exactly half the amount that <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> initially had sought. The increase would be funded through reductions in other spending programs that would be 0.43 percent if applied across-the-board. Under the plan, however, appropriations subcommittees would be able to pick and choose among programs, allowing some to escape the full brunt of the cuts. Many elements of the president's crime-fighting package are contained in the drug strategy, but some highly controversial elements are missing and the administration has been pushing for action on them. They include applying the death penalty to a wider range of crimes than under current law. Another key provision would place limits on the number of appeals that could be filed by certain prisoners, and a third would ease restrictions on how police and prosecutors obtain certain kinds of evidence.
</TEXT>
