<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> joined a galaxy of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> celebrities Tuesday night in paying tribute to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> on the 24th anniversary of the federal arts legislation that gave it birth. Eyeing the black-tie crowd that included actors <PERSON> Charlton </PERSON> <PERSON> Heston </PERSON>, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairbanks </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Travolta </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Reeve </PERSON> and actresses <PERSON> Marlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON>, master of ceremonies <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON> crowed: `` Welcome to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, the entertainment capital of the world.'' <PERSON> Valenti </PERSON>, the longtime head of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and onetime <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide to <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, added, `` There are things that happen here that a <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> scriptwriter would give his life to be able to put down.'' It was <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> who signed the legislation on Sept. 29, 1965, creating the National Endowments for the Arts and the Humanities, which two years later spawned the independent, non-profit <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. The institute has been a leader in efforts to preserve motion pictures and television, and trains young directors through a program in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> joined in the entertainment at the gala at the National Building Museum, following a string of celebrities who repeated famous movie lines. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, looking across the ballroom to his wife <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> at a table 30 yards away, repeated <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogart </PERSON>'s toast from `` Casablanca'': `` Here's looking at ya, kid!'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called film `` the mirror of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> ... and also in a sense the conscience of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' He cited such films as `` Coal Miner's Daughter,'' `` Hoosiers,'' and several recent movies that portrayed drugs in a bad lights, including `` Lean On Me,'' `` Clean and Sober'' and `` Dancing As Fast As I Can. `` I want to thank the film industry for helping stop this terrible threat to our kids. ... I welcome your leadership,'' said the president.
