<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> teen-ager was arrested Tuesday on charges of selling the crack cocaine that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> displayed on television to illustrate the seriousness of the nation's drug problems. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 18, was indicted earlier in the day by a federal grand jury on four counts of unlawfully distributing crack and one count of using a telephone to help arrange an alleged sale. The alleged distribution started in April, on one occasion near <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> in July, according to the indictment. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was picked up at his home in southeast <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> by city police and <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> agents, said <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Cornelius </PERSON> <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Magistrate <PERSON> Pattrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Attridge </PERSON> ordered <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> held without bond pending another hearing Wednesday. In a Sept. 5 televised speech, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> held up a clear plastic bag containing a handful of crack nuggets and said they had been seized across the street from the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> a few days previously. The alleged dealer was lured to <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> _ not one of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s drug markets _ four days before by undercover drug agents after <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> staffers asked for a sample from the vicinity of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to show that dealing could happen anywhere. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> said they had planned to make the purchase a few blocks away before the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> request. The transaction with an undercover <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agent was photographed, but the dealer was not taken into custody then because agents hoped he would sell a larger amount later and identify his supply organization, officials said. A planned arrest last week fell through when the suspect did not show up.
