<HEAD>Beirutis Flock Home, Glad But Impoverished After Refugee Ordeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A million refugees have flooded back into <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> after six months of fighting, many impoverished by their ordeal and some fearful lest the savage shelling flares up again. Long lines of cars began streaming into the shattered capital within minutes of the announcement Friday by <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> leader Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> that he was accepting an Arab League cease-fire. Hundreds more Lebanese booked passage for the three-hour ferry crossing from <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> to the Christian port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION>, while others flew into the newly reopened <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> airport. The six months of fighting killed at least 929 people and wounded 2,741. <PERSON> Issam </PERSON> <PERSON> Baydoun </PERSON>, a Sunni Moslem bank employee who fled during the shelling battles that pitted <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s mainly Christian fighters against <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and its Moslem militia allies, was among the returnees. `` I have spent most of my 30 years' savings during the 2 -LCB- months of forced migration to the south,'' said the 55-year-old father of two. <PERSON> Baydoun </PERSON> said he fled his <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> home in a seven-story apartment building in the heavily shelled district of <PERSON> Ras </PERSON> <PERSON> el-Nabeh </PERSON> in July, when `` things could not be borne anymore.'' `` My wife had started taking sedatives,'' he said. `` My daughter screamed every time a shell crashed nearby or because of the sound of a rocket passing overhead.'' Just like many other west Beirutis, <PERSON> Baydoun </PERSON> headed south. He rented a two-room house for $ 900 a month in <LOCATION> Iqlim </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kharroub </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Chouf </LOCATION> mountains. `` In all, I spent $ 3,000 in only 75 days of exile,'' he said. `` Believe me, now that we're back I ca n't afford to restore my shell-pocked house.'' Asked whether he would be able to rent another house in the south if fighting broke out again, <PERSON> Baydoun </PERSON> said: `` I am a conscientious employee and have a good reputation at the bank. The bank manager might be willing to lend me some money on temporary basis. But to tell you the truth, God knows when I will be able to pay him back.'' He was glad to be back, albeit impoverished, saying `` there's no place like home.'' The Baydouns' neighborhood is in a section of west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> where <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and its allies installed their advance artillery batteries. On the opposite side are <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s troops as well as Christian militants from the Lebanese Forces. East Beirut residents also breathed relief when the Arab league commitee announced the opening of all crossings linking both sectors of the capital, the lifting of the 6-month-old blockade of the Christian heartland and the opening of the airport. `` May God guide them to the right path,'' said <PERSON> Samira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gobril </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> housewife who expressed hope that the leaders of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s factions would work together for a durable peace. `` May God keep utmost in their minds the plight of the poor population.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Gobril </PERSON>, 38, and mother of an 11-year-old boy and an 8-year-old girl, lives in the frequently battered Christian area of <LOCATION> Ashrafieh </LOCATION> a few miles from the Green Line that divides east from west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. She had fled to the fashionable mountain resort of <LOCATION> Faraya </LOCATION>, 20 miles to the northeast. `` This time we could afford it,'' she added, but `` it'll take my husband five years of hard work to recoup the amount of money we have spent during the last four months.'' Police said at least 1 million refugees who fled <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> have returned since Friday. <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> took the brunt of the shelling, forcing all but 150,000 of its remaining 1.5 million people to flee. Some of those that did not travel to safer areas of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> took the ferry to <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, either to wait out the fighting or to apply for American, Canadian, Australian and other visas as a gateway to a new life away from their country, shattered by 14 years of civil war. Estimates vary. Immigration officials in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> say about 20,000 Lebanese are on the small east <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island whose population numbers just 691,000. But relief agency officials working to ease the refugees' plight said the actual number of Lebanese in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> probably reached 30,000 at the height of the fighting and perhaps more. The Christian refugees' only exit to the outside world has been through a hydrofoil ferry service from the port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION> on the south <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> coast. Moslems, too, have been fleeing to <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, though they are still a minority of the Lebanese refugees on the island.
