<DATELINE>POMONA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most everyone has heard of killer bees and killer whales _ but what about killer snails? One man is determined to prove that the combative cousins of common garden snails are the answer to eliminating the slow-moving but voracious plant munchers. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrie </PERSON>, 34, sells a hostile snail breed that he claims will prey on the garden pests. `` It's the tough new snail on the block,'' <PERSON> Harrie </PERSON> said the other day from his demonstration booth at the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fair </LOCATION>. The shell-less critters ambush garden snails, following their slime trails and attacking them when they lay their eggs, <PERSON> Harrie </PERSON> said. The bloodthirsty snails, known to scientists as Rumina decollata, usually leave their victims mortally wounded, rather than killing them outright, he said. <PERSON> Harrie </PERSON>, who sells the attack snails for $ 20 per 100, claims they're too slow-moving to move from the garden to the house, and pose no danger to children and pets.
