 The Metropolitan Opera chose `` Aida'' as its opening night opera and gave it a dream cast. <PERSON> Aprile </PERSON> <PERSON> Millo </PERSON>, heralded as the next great <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON> soprano, sang the title role on Monday night. Not content just to pour out her voice of grandeur, she used shading, held notes and pianissimo and acted the slave to <LOCATION> Amneris </LOCATION> that Aida is. Seldom has a Met Opera Aida been so often on her knees. <PERSON> Placido </PERSON> <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON>, the Radames when this production was new last December, sang Radames again. His voice was beautiful in tone, smooth in production, sometimes ringing, occasionally tense and harder-edged than it formerly was. He does n't scoop up to high notes, as most tenors do, in `` Celeste Aida.'' The final love duet, when both inserted tenderness into their generous-size voices, was thrilling. <PERSON> Dolora </PERSON> <PERSON> Zajick </PERSON>, who made her Met debut last fall, sang a notable Amneris. She's a mezzo soprano but has a delivery like a soprano and a confident stage presence. Some Amnerises are almost unnoticed. When the two were together, this Amneris commanded more attention than Aida. As <PERSON> Aida </PERSON> was subservient, the king's daughter <PERSON> Amneris </PERSON> was regal. Miss <PERSON> Zajick </PERSON>'s voice also conveyed <PERSON> Amneris </PERSON>' love, making her a sympathetic character. <PERSON> Paata </PERSON> <PERSON> Burchuladze </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S.S.R. </LOCATION>, was making his Met debut as the high priest. <PERSON> Burchuladze </PERSON>, a winner in the 1985 <PERSON> Luciano </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> voice competition in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, has the deep notes and dark sound Americans expect and adore from Russian basses. He has sung `` <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Godunov </PERSON>'' in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sherrill </PERSON> <PERSON> Milnes </PERSON> sang <PERSON> Aida </PERSON>'s father with urgency _ he's concerned with the Egypt-Ethiopia war, not with love. <PERSON> Milnes </PERSON> also sang with a beautiful tone, which characterized all the principals. The triumphal entry scene included a couple of horses and, for once in a Met production, no eccentricity. Three young dancers in Act 2 were pleasing. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> conducted with understanding. The production, by <PERSON> Sonja </PERSON> <PERSON> Frisell </PERSON>, twice uses the device of moving a set by elevator, thereby revealing the next set either above or below it. This is dramatic and effective. The first time it was done, going from <PERSON> Amneris </PERSON>' rooms to a public square full of Egyptians, the audience gasped with appreciation. Though some were well gowned, women in the opening night audience provided less a fashion show than in some years.
