<FIRST>r a PM-ShuttleMishap     09-26 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Mishap,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Water Mishap May Not Delay Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investigators hope <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s next scheduled space mission wo n't be delayed by damage caused by a surge of fire protection water that sprayed the shuttle. `` I have not given up launching on the 18th,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Utsman </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> who heads the investigation into Sunday's accident. <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> is scheduled for liftoff on Dec. 18. <PERSON> Utsman </PERSON> said Monday the problem started when a valve failed, and then two workers in their haste to shut off the system mistakenly turned on most of the sprinklers. `` I'm chalking it up to a combination of equipment error and human error,'' he said. `` The guys who did it were only trying to help. ... Good intentions sometimes go wrong.'' As many as 200 of the shuttle's 500 woven fiberglass heat shields may have to be replaced, he said. The blankets, about the size of a beach towel, protect the top of the shuttle `` The thermal blankets are our major concern,'' <PERSON> Utsman </PERSON> said. He said initial inspection revealed no damage to any of the more than 20,000 silica thermal tiles. These are much smaller and tougher than the blankets and are bonded to side and bottom areas of the shuttle subjected to the highest heat. While there appeared to be no damage to electrical or electronic systems, `` we wo n't know for sure until we power up the vehicle,'' <PERSON> Utsman </PERSON> said. He said investigators should know within a few days if the launch will be delayed. `` If we have to replace only a couple hundred blankets, there should n't be a hit,'' <PERSON> Utsman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Utsman </PERSON> said the accident occurred Sunday after three workers performed routine maintenance on the water sprinkler system in the building where the shuttle was being processed. When the workers finished the job, they tested the system by pressurizing it, but a gate valve that they were certain was closed failed and water began flowing from sprinklers in one of six safety zones. `` Two other workers who tried to help inadvertently turned on the other sprinklers'' and water poured onto work platforms and splashed onto the shuttle, <PERSON> Utsman </PERSON> said. Other workers were able to quickly turn off the water. He did not know the amount of water released. He said a small amount of water leaked into the closed cargo bay but did n't damage electronic systems there. He said no water entered the crew cabin.
</TEXT>
