<SECOND>PM-Direct Mail, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>You Want to Buy the Names of 146,983 Biology Majors?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You know all that junk mail that falls through your mail slot every day? If the envelope is just plain brown, it breaks <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON>'s heart. <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> is a sales representative for the <ORGANIZATION> Tension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Envelope </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a firm which produces about one-fifth of all the envelopes used by the direct mail industry. His territory is central <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and he single-handedly sells 100 million envelopes a year, enough to fill 70 semi-trailers. Direct mail is big business, getting bigger. Tension Envelope has plants in 11 cities, many working two or three shifts, six days a week, making envelopes, headed for your mailbox. <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> was selling envelopes here Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> Direct </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s 72nd annual conference and exhibition, which attracted 8,000 people in the direct mail and telephone selling business and the people who serve them, like <PERSON> Garland </PERSON>. `` A plain brown envelope is insane,'' said <PERSON> Garland </PERSON>. `` The biggest opportunity for blowing the product's whistle is lost.'' He stood before a display of envelopes that were anything but plain. Some had rippled edges _ `` zippers'' to the trade _ that all but compel the recipient to open the envelope, which is the point. The latest wrinkle in envelopes is one in which the address flap flips over, allowing the recipient to reply using the original envelope. It saves storage space, <PERSON> Garland </PERSON> explained: `` If you insert a return envelope into the outgoing envelope, and you're using a million envelopes a month, you've got to find space for 2 million envelopes, not 1 million.'' Direct marketing likes big numbers. Some 88.5 million Americans, it brags, bought something through the mail in 1988, and the average mail-order purchase amounted to $ 74. The compilation of mailing lists, as might be imagined, is big business because `` targeting'' _ sending the pitch to the most likely customer _ is the name of the game. The American <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> List </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Neck </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, offers lists of students from kindergarten through graduate school. For $ 50 a thousand, you can buy the names and home and school addresses of 146,983 biology majors. <ORGANIZATION> PCS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mailing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> List </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is even more specialized. It will sell you the names and addresses of 11,438 air traffic controllers, 16,600 subscribers to Tax Angles; 15,547 auto wheel and frame alignment shops; 1,381 disc jockeys; 7,260 T-shirt stores; 425,000 `` high income women''; 10,620 hair and wig dealers or 532,390 professors. And National Demographics and <ORGANIZATION> Lifestyles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, pitching its `` relevant'' lists in a comic book, refers to folks who respond to direct marketing as `` respondoids'' and describes them as `` ever hopeful yet enslaved mail responsive mortals'' who `` long to fill out questionnaires about themselves and receive relevant mail.'' National Demographics gathers its lists from respondoids who fill out those consumer questionnaires or product registration cards that come with new hair dryers and toasters. Only 7 percent, the company says, check the little box indicating they want to be on no one's mail list. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Caugherty </PERSON>, director of the association's Shop at Home Information Center, says most people like direct marketing. The 3,500-member association has developed codes of conduct to protect those who do n't. A 15-page pamphlet spells out the ethics of the business -LRB- `` free'' should mean `` a product or service which is offered without cost or obligation'' -RRB-. Another, aimed at policing those telephone sales calls, says the callers should not make offers `` in the guise of research or a survey when the real intent is to sell products or services or to raise funds.'' As for the latest twist, telephone machines which make a recorded sales pitch, the rules say `` a live operator'' should first introduce the recorded message. Moreover, the guidelines say, calls should n't be made `` during hours which are unreasonable to the recipients.'' Whether that's supper time, the guidelines do n't say.
