<HEAD>Former Reagan Official Disputes Warnings on Hispanics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Republican <PERSON> Hispanic </PERSON> says conditions for Hispanic youth are n't as bad as described by a federal study and by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>, who served at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, provoked strong disagreement with her testimony at a hearing on Hispanic children Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION>, Youth and Families. She disputed remarks Education Secretary <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> made last week when he released a report on school dropouts and said the rate among Hispanic students is `` a national tragedy.'' `` The future looks quite good for individual Hispanics,'' said <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON>. `` Native-born Hispanics, despite the ominous report from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, appear to be staying in school longer,'' she said. She challenged the statistical basis for the report and said the department's finding, like other statistical studies of Hispanics, were skewed by large influxes of recent immigrants _ arriving at a rate she estimated at 400,000 a year. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> said Hispanic immigrants will eventually move into the economic mainstream as have earlier <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> immigrants, who also faced high dropout rates in their first generations. The studies `` diminish the very real and significant progress'' of Hispanics in this country. Her remarks put her at odds, however, with a panel of Hispanic experts appearing with her before the committee, who cited severe poverty and education problems among Hispanics. `` She's not right,'' said <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosewater </PERSON>, staff director of the committee, following the hearing. `` They -LRB- other expert witnesses -RRB- made a very clear point. There's lots of research showing not just first generation, but second and third generation -LRB- Hispanics -RRB- are not doing well in school.'' <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinojosa </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> said Hispanics of varying national origins are falling further behind economically. He said Hispanics have been hurt by discrimination, low educational achievement and changes in the national labor market that have reduced the availability of middle-income jobs. He said the higher fertility rate among Hispanics is a more important factor than the arrival of recent immigrants. Committee Chairman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., said Hispanics face `` severe poverty'' and `` incredible disparity'' with other ethnic groups, regardless of the statistics used `` The numbers are overwhelming,'' he said. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> is a senior fellow with the <ORGANIZATION> Manhattan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> research organization, and is a former unsuccessful <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>.
