<HEAD>Bush's Global Ban Unlikely to Fly in Libya, Iran</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chemical weapons proposal might play in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> but his call for a global ban is not likely to get much of a hearing in <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which are thought to possess the grisly substances, experts say. Addressing the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Monday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proclaimed readiness to destroy 80 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> chemical weapons if <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> follows suit, and urged other nations to sign a multilateral pact to outlaw them entirely. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal `` made virtue of necessity,'' said one senior senator, because in 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed a law requiring the destruction of all old chemical weapons by 1997, while authorizing production of a new generation. `` I consider it a good, positive move,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` Getting the Soviets to join in would be very good, and if both superpowers lead the way bilaterally, I think it will give some impetus to the overall world move in that direction _ which is the ultimate objective.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are the only two states to acknowledge having chemical weapons, although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that as many as 20 nations possess or have the capability of producing them. Experts have estimated up to a dozen nations can make chemical weapons. There was no explanation from the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> for the figure of 20 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> used. Delegates to the 40-Nation Conference on Disarmament ended their most recent meeting in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> last month without any indication of an agreement on a chemical weapons ban. The conference, which meets again in November, is stalled on the issue of how to monitor the production of chemical weapons, which experts say can be made in factories similar to those that make fertilizer or other compounds. Also in dispute are the size of chemical weapons stockpiles, and even the number of countries that have them. The extent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stockpile is classified, although private analysts estimate it at 30,000 tons. Soviet spokesman said their government had `` no more than 50,000 tons of chemical warfare agents.'' It may take more than a superpower deal, however, to provide rid the planet of chemical weapons, according to two private arms control experts in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal `` might focus international attention on chemical weapons and lead to a multilateral treaty,'' said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Feinstein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a disarmament lobby in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. But it may instead produce a U.S.-Soviet agreement and divert attention from production by other countries, he said. <PERSON> Elisa </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, called <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s call `` a pretty disappointing response from a president who has committed himself to eliminating chemical weapons from the face of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>.'' She said it was unlikely to win the support of <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERS