<TEXT>
 Residents who got their first look at the devastation wrought by Hurricane Hugo say it will be years before this barrier island returns to being a quaint seaside village. `` On a normal day, this was like being in heaven,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Traywick </PERSON>, whose first floor was buried under an inch of muck. `` It's not like that any more,'' <PERSON> Traywick </PERSON> said. `` Not for a long time.'' The island, heavily damaged by wind and water and cut off from the mainland because of a downed bridge, was declared under martial law. Island officials on Monday began a daily ferry service allowing some residents to return home for a few hours. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON>'s 135 mph winds bashed the island, located across the harbor from <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, and a wall of water swept through homes and businesses. Few houses were left undamaged, most of the taller trees were felled and huge potholes were scooped out of the roads. The beach has shifted, and the entire marina dock was torn loose from its pilings and swept to nearby <LOCATION> Goat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. `` It looks like what happens after artillery fire,'' said resident <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> officer who served in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> during World War II. For many residents, angry at what they consider government inaction in getting them on the island, it was a relief to see what <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> had wrought. `` I'm glad to know what the situation is,'' said <PERSON> Traywick </PERSON>. `` At least I know. Now we can sit down and get started on some plans.'' For <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bozzelli </PERSON>, it would n't have made much difference when he got to the island. His house, now split open like an overripe melon, is about 50 yards from where it was last week. `` I pretty well figured it might be gone,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> began work Monday on a temporary pontoon bridge linking Isle of Palms, and adjacent <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, to the mainland. Isle of Palms City Councilman <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neal </PERSON> said that should give most residents of the islands land access by week's end. Monday afternoon, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> barges transported bulldozers to the island to clear the fallen trees. Most residents said they would return to rebuild, even with the first-hand knowledge of what a powerful hurricane can do. `` I think most people will be back,'' said <PERSON> Muriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, who owns a house and a rental duplex on the island. `` It's like an addiction, the laid-back style and the quiet.'' <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, manager of the Sea Cabins development that once existed on the beach, said the cabins would be rebuilt. `` It's the tranquillity of the island when it's not under a storm seige,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` It'll be back to that one of these days.''
