<SECOND>PM-China,0931</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jiang Denies Suppression Of Pro-Democracy Movement A Tragedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemin </PERSON> today denied that the military suppression of the pro-democracy movement was a tragedy, calling the assault an unavoidable response to an attempt to overthrow the government. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, in his first news conference since being named to head the 48-million member party in June, also indicated that the party had yet to decide whether <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s supreme leader, will be allowed to retire from his last official post. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> was joined by the other five members of the <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the ruling party's top decision-making group, including conservative Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>. Some 400 Chinese and foreign reporters attended the conference, which was broadcast live on national television. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, a former party boss in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> who replaced the ousted reformist <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> on June 24, said of the June clash between pro-democracy protesters and the army: `` We believe it was not a tragedy.'' He called the pro-democracy movement a `` counter-revolutionary rebellion aimed at negating the leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> and overthrowing the socialist system.'' The June 3-4 military attack on student-led protesters in central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was unavoidable, he said, because of foreign forces trying to undermine <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s socialist system and a handful of people within <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> who `` engaged in all kinds of conspiracies in an attempt to overthrow the existing government.'' The army killed hundreds of unarmed civilians in the assault. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, 63, who reportedly has been named by <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> to succeed him as top leader when he leaves the political scene, said `` much is at stake'' in the question of when the 85-year-old <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> should leave his last post, as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. He noted that <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> had on numerous occasions expressed a wish to pass on power to a new generation, but it was still up to the party and state to decide when the architect of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s past decade of economic reforms can step down. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> did not mention a party decision, revealed in May by <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, to continue accepting <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s leadership on major issues regardless of his formal resignation from all but the military post. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s resignation from that post would not be likely to alter his position as the final arbiter of political matters, but would reflect his efforts to put in place successors he trusts. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> acknowledged that the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which could make a formal ruling on <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s retirement, will be meeting soon to map out economic development plans for the next two or three years. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> and the others refused to answer repeated questions on the number of people arrested and executed in the crackdown on dissent. <PERSON> Qiao </PERSON> <PERSON> Shi </PERSON>, who is responsible for legal matters within the party, said `` we have dealt with some people'' but all those executed were convicted of serious crimes. He said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has acted prudently toward students and intellectuals and called a foreign report of 120,000 arrests since June `` unfounded nonsense.'' <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, told by a reporter that a woman student had been sent to the countryside after participating in the pro-democracy movement and been raped there by peasants, described the case as `` a fairy tale out of The Arabian Nights.'' He stressed that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s policy toward students who demanded democratic reform was `` to unite them and educate them.'' Since taking office <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> has pressed for greater attention to ideological matters, particularly among young people. He indicated that in this way he could escape the fate of his two predecessors, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> and the late <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON>. Both were purged for failing to combat Western liberal ideas while trying to open <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> up to the world. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> declined to say what will happen to <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>. He said the party was `` making further investigations'' into charges <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> supported the pro-democracy movement and thus split the party. Both <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> and <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s rival for power, blamed <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> for letting the political unrest get out of hand, but <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>'s tone indicated <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> may escape criminal charges. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> said the party recognized that <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> had done some positive things in his nine years as premier and party general secretary. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, who has not been seen in public since he went to central Tiananmen Square on May 19 to talk to student hunger strikers, is leading a `` quiet and comfortable life,'' <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> added that since <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> had served the party longer than he had: `` He enjoys better treatment, in fact he enjoys a better salary than me.'' On other topics, Vice Premier <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilin </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, reiterated that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will stick to such economic reforms as developing export-oriented industries along the coast. He said private enterprise would continue to play a `` necessary and beneficial supplemental role'' in the socialist economy but added that `` appropriate restrictions'' would check the growth of private industry. Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> spoke at length on corruption, a major issue during the spring protests, saying the party was taking the lead by cracking down on nepotism, use of luxury imported cars, overseas trips, gift-giving and banqueting at public expense. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, like the other five speakers, was dressed in a dark Western suit and tie. A former student in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> who also speaks good English, he used a Russian phrase in answering a question from a Soviet journalist and used English words on several occasions.
