<HEAD>Report: FAA's Tighter Security Still Not In Place</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to include Collins' first name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional investigators say that almost a year after a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> jet exploded over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> ca n't say that its promised tighter security precautions are in place. Airlines are not meeting their security requirements and the training of security workers appears to be the biggest problem, according to a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report that was summarized Monday by a congresswoman. `` <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has not established minimum training standards needed to ensure that airline security personnel working at high risk airports overseas are sufficiently trained to carry out required security measures,'' Rep. <PERSON> Cardiss </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, D-Ill., quoted <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, as saying <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said the full report would remain secret, but she said investigators found the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> `` can not assure itself that required security procedures are being properly carried out by the airlines at designated high-risk airports.'' Airlines are responsible for security at airport gates, generally using guidelines set by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>. The airports considered high-risk for Americans were identified during the hearing as those in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. Two hundred seventy people died when <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103, which started in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and stopped in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, blew up over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, last Dec. 21. Investigators found the mid-air explosion was caused by a bomb in a radio cassette player. The Syrian-backed Popular Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> is considered the prime suspect behind the act, though the group's leader has denied involvement. Witnesses told the hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Government Operations government activities and transportation subcommittee, which <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> chairs, that intelligence about anti-American groups likely to attack airlines is n't good enough. `` Security begins with an understanding of the threat it faces; our intelligence services must provide this understanding,'' said <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> expert on terrorism, now president of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` They do n't do it especially well, and it is n't especially easy to do,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> should have an independent intelligence capability.'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON>, managing director of corporate security of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the government should take more responsibility for combatting travel dangers and should share some intelligence with airlines. `` Information like the types of passports these groups are using,'' <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON> said. `` When information is floating around that a group is planning something, we should be told.'' <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> was fined recently for alleged security lapses at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Frankfort </LOCATION>'s airport, including failure to properly screen passengers, improperly checking some carry-on baggage and failure to search cargo areas before loading. About a dozen members of two organizations of family members of passengers on Flight 103 also told the congressional panel the government should get tougher on security. `` Placing responsibility for security procedures in the hands of airlines is a conflict of interest,'' said testimony prepared by the <ORGANIZATION> Victims </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103. `` Airlines are in the business to make money. Precious dollars are cut from vital security budgets to raise bottom-line profits.''
