<HEAD>Troubled Former Temptation Jailed After Showing up Late to Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge ordered former Temptations lead singer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON> to jail because he showed up five hours late for a hearing. <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON>, who was in court on a probation violation charge, was scheduled for a 9 a.m. hearing Monday before Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>. When <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON> arrived just before 2 p.m., <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> ordered <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON> to spend the night in jail and said the court would take up the matter today. `` It would look better if he had shown up on time, but there's hope,'' said <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> Monday's hearing was scheduled to decide if <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON> should undergo drug treatment instead of serving a jail sentence. <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON>, 48, was convicted in May 1988 of misdemeanor possession of cocaine. His sentence included two years' probation, 50 days of community service and drug testing and treatment. A drug test last week was positive for opiates, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON> was arrested Sept. 16, the third time this year he has been in court for probation violations. Last week, <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON> denied he had a drug problem, then admitted it later. The judge had postponed deciding <PERSON> Ruffin </PERSON>'s case until Monday, so <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> could check into the price and availability of a drug-treatment center in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
