<FIRST>r a PM-NYCPoliceCommissioner     09-26 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Police Commissioner,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, the city's first black police commissioner, has resigned after almost six years, leaving a legacy of innovation despite budget constraints, a tough war on drugs and his own verbal gaffes. `` I'm not always right,'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> once said, `` but I'm never dull.'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, 63, cited chronic asthma in a resignation letter sent Monday to Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>. His departure is effective Oct. 22. During <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s time in office, crime rates soared and city streets got more violent, fueled by crack. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said combating the drug war was his `` highest priority from the start,'' noting that the Narcotics Division grew almost five-fold during his term, which began Jan. 1, 1984. He also created Tactical Narcotics Teams that are deployed to crack-ridden neighborhoods. But, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> added in his letter, `` I must acknowledge that the greatest problem when I came in is even more serious as I depart. ... The plague of illegal drugs that has wreaked such tragedy, violence and crime.'' <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, who called <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> `` one of the greatest police commissioners that ever served,'' appointed First Deputy Commissioner <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Condon </PERSON> _ <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s own choice _ as commissioner. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, who lost his bid for re-election in September's Democratic primary to <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> Borough President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, leaves office at the end of the year. <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> indicated before the primary that he wanted to resign but waited at the mayor's request. He said <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> would return to private life, but would not elaborate. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> has been working since June on his memoirs, tentatively titled `` Cop,'' to be published next fall. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> ran afoul of some black groups in July 1987 when he called black crime against blacks `` our little dirty secret.'' The next month, he apologized publicly for saying to a woman who spoke at a town meeting about being afraid of rapists: `` You're out here tonight. You ca n't be too frightened. You're the kind he's looking for, under 30, beautiful, blonde. In apologizing for what he called that `` insensitive'' remark, <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said the woman had been heckling him and that he had taken asthma medication that `` may hype me up.'' <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> joined the force in 1951 as the first black police officer in a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> precinct. `` I think they were surprised to see me,'' he recalled in 1984. `` I had an Irish name, and I came from a predominantly white veterans' housing project in <LOCATION> Bath </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, but when they saw me, they developed a sudden shortage of lockers at the precinct house.'' By the time he was through, the positions he held included detective, head of the internal legal department, commissioner for community affairs, city traffic commissioner, state correction commissioner, chief of the city housing police and city correction commissioner. The commissioner oversaw a department with 26,790 officers. In resigning, he noted that it had grown by 2,129 officers during his tenure and that the number of black officers rose 17 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Hispanics </ORGANIZATION> 60 percent and women 85 percent. The uniformed force now is 11 percent black, 11.5 percent Hispanic and 12.4 percent female, he said. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> also cited increased educational requirements for certain ranks, a `` stronger stand'' on domestic violence and a program to put officers back on foot patrol in all 75 precincts.
</TEXT>
