<HEAD>Newspapers Coped With Getting the News Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH GROAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Newspapers in cities pummeled by Hurricane Hugo found the storm was a journalist's dream and a publisher's nightmare as they labored to get out the big story without power, water or passable roads Most papers in the storm's path through <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> managed to keep printing, but it was n't easy. In <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, The State newspaper temporarily housed two other papers. The staff of the <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> papers did n't go home for several nights. In <LOCATION> Myrtle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, The Sun News staff used portable toilets because the city sewers were out of commission. `` We got the paper out -LRB- Friday -RRB- and have been doing it ever since,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, an editor at The News and Courier and The Evening Post in hard-hit <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. `` A couple of nights everyone slept on the floor at the newspaper,'' <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> said. `` We did n't smell too good.'' The newspaper's emergency generator provided enough electricity to run the printing press, computers and a few lights, but the staff was still without running water Monday. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> struck <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> late Thursday, killing at least 17 people and leaving more than $ 3 billion in damage. Some papers were able to gather and print the information their readers needed to cope during the storm's aftermath, but could n't manage delivery In <LOCATION> Georgetown </LOCATION>, 10-foot waves lapped up against the windows of the <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. Two delivery vans were swallowed up, and employees delivered the paper in their own cars. Saturday's paper was delayed one day because the newspaper building was blacked out Friday. The storm was `` a journalist's dream, but at the same time a nightmare,'' said <PERSON> Ral