ng up a political party and supporting Mrs. <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>. But while the electoral process seems to be drawing in the opposition and weakening the armed resistance, the Sandinista platform slogan, `` Everything Will Be Better,'' exposed a crack in an otherwise slick surface. The slogan is a reminder, if any were needed, that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s economy has gone steadily downhill, to the point that it rivals <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> as the poorest nation in the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION> In an effort to control hyperinflation, the government has had to implement an austerity program that left thousands jobless. The Sandinistas blame their problems on the war and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic boycott, but promises of better times ahead are being met with skepticism by voters who must struggle daily to make ends meet with less money, higher prices and food shortages. It was no surprise that <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> were renominated; they have worked together smoothly in the past. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> is the tough, firebrand ex-guerrilla who does n't miss a chance to bait the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, while <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> is the cool, moderate-toned, polished intellectual. In his acceptance speech, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> predicted the Sandinista would win and that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` will have to accept an understanding with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has already given signs of accommodation; recently a top <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official visited <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and met with <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, the first time that has happened in years. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> knows that winning <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> acceptance, however reluctant, is probably vital to economic recovery, but also that this depends on his party winning the elections cleanly. The Sandinistas are intent on having the vote declared free and fair and have invited international observers including former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, who monitored <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s presidential election in May and called it a fraud. In an editorial, Mrs. <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>'s newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s speech showed the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> were depending on `` sterile anti-Americanism'' and did not have a vision of the future to sell the electorate. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is trying to devise a way to assist <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s fledgling democratic process without providing direct support to the opposition. A figure of $ 9 million has been mentioned by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressional sources; that would be more than $ 4 for each of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s 1.9 million voters, but there are no signs of any big money yet. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> has already called on its organizations, which cover every neighborhood in the country, to begin house-to-house campaigning, using the threat of a super-financed opposition for motivation. The well-planned Sandinista convention, to which the press and the diplomatic corps were invited, contrasted sharply with tense deliberations of the political parties comprising the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> UNO </ORGANIZATION>, as it is known for its Spanish initials, chose <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> as Mrs. <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>'s running mate three weeks ago, but the choice almost split the coalition. The choice was considered important because m