<HEAD>Three Arrested For Allegedly Holding Woman in Slavery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AZUSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three people accused of kidnapping a Guatemalan woman and keeping her enslaved for a year through torture and rape have been arrested, authorities said. Two women, ages 28 and 32, and a man, 37, were arrested Monday night after an informant's tip sent detectives to a camper truck that matched the description of the one where the victim was chained each night, said sheriff's Lt. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>. The woman escaped Sept. 2 by stealing keys from her sleeping captors. `` She tried to escape once before but was beaten,'' said police Detective <PERSON> Delia </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>. The 27-year-old woman told police she was kidnapped July 15, 1988, when a woman approached her at a bus stop and lured her into the camper with the promise of a job. She was raped, tortured with electrical shocks and forced to cook and clean for a man, two women and five children, police said. At night, she was chained in the camper outside the group's home. Six children, ranging in age from infancy to 8 or 9 years old, were taken into protective custody at the time of the arrests, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said. Authorities withheld the names of the adults booked by <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> police for investigation of kidnapping, he said. Police said they do not doubt the victim's story. `` When I first read the report I said, ` Aw, come on, these things do n't happen,''' said police Detective <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Heidesch </PERSON>. `` But several of us talked to the victim independently, a counselor talked to her and everyone is convinced she is telling the truth.''
