<HEAD>Soldiers Glad To Be Home, Worry About Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To ADD background on earlier withdrawals INSERT two grafs after
17th, ```My officers ... change.''' Picks up 18th pvs, `Some soldiers ...'
^With PM-Cambodia-Vietnam, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOC BAI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten years ago, <PERSON> Linh </PERSON> <PERSON> Trang </PERSON> was one of the first Vietnamese soldiers to enter <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in a surprise invasion that toppled the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> government in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION>. `` It was hell in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, 10 years of it,'' said <PERSON> Trang </PERSON>, 33, who commanded a battallion in the guerrilla-infested jungles of western <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. `` I'm just glad to be going home.'' This morning, those 10 years in hell ended as <PERSON> Trang </PERSON> and 10,000 other troops marched home through the gates of this sleepy border town. Up and down the border, Vietnamese troops are coming home in what the <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> government says is the withdrawal of its last 26,000 troops in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Returning by ship, ferry, truck and on foot, the soldiers faced a government-orchestrated hero's welcome today but an uncertain future. Like many of his comrades, <PERSON> Trang </PERSON> was stricken by malaria during the war. He also said he's lost 15 pounds, which means a lot to his small frame. But, he said, none of his health problems concern him. What is important now is to find a job. Last week, the chief spokesman of the <ORGANIZATION> Vietnamese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> would demobilize an unspecificied number of solidiers after its war with <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Major Gen. <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Thai </PERSON> said returning veterans would be given preference in finding work and economic assistance if they had difficulties. But many wonder whether <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, which is one of the poorest countries in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and already faces an unemployment crisis, will be able to provide jobs for the returning soldiers. `` I am not a young man,'' said <PERSON> Trang </PERSON>, `` so I do n't think I can return to school. I want to work in textiles, maybe as a tailor. Before I entered the army I was a tailor in <LOCATION> Ho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.'' Still, he said, nothing had been settled. <PERSON> Luon </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dang </PERSON> is a little more sure about what he wants to do but just as worried. The 23-year-old from Can <PERSON> Tho </PERSON> province says he will try to stay in the armed forces, his home for the last five years. `` I like a soldier's life,'' he said as he squatted in the buffer zone between <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. `` I lost my family during the Vietnam War so the army is my family. They feed me and clothe me. I believe in them.'' <PERSON> Dang </PERSON> said he hoped he would not be demobilized. `` My officers know I love the Vietnamese Army,'' he said, `` but after I walk through the gate to my country over there everything could change.'' <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> has demobilized more than a half-million soldiers in recent years, Gen. <PERSON> Tran </PERSON> <PERSON> Cong </PERSON> <PERSON> Man </PERSON>, editor of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s official army newspaper, said in a recent interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He said the armed forces' manpower peak was 1.5 million in 1979, 50,000 were demobilized between 1982 and 1987, and over the past two years <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> had released 500,000. Some soldiers said they will miss <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Earlier last week, at a good-bye ceremony at <LOCATION> Pursat </LOCATION>, a provincial <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> capital, <PERSON> Cao </PERSON> <PERSON> Viet </PERSON> sat weeping in the corner as he hugged a Cambodian brother-in-arms. `` We are very close to the people in the countryside,'' said the Vietnamese officer who spent six years in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and speaks good Khmer. `` We died for these people and they know it. I will never forget the people here.'' Behind him, a Cambodian cultural troupe played salsa music. Vietnamese soldiers danced with <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> women. Bottles of Western scotch were passed from hand to hand. Fighting in the jungles was difficult, <PERSON> Viet </PERSON> said. Lack of transportation makes for shortages of drinking water and food. Many nights he and his men went hungry, he said. `` A guerrilla enemy is very hard to destroy,'' <PERSON> Viet </PERSON> said. `` They would attack and then disperse and chasing them with difficult.'' The Vietnamese Army began as a guerrilla force when it battled the French and American armies but it used more traditional methods in fighting its war in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Viet </PERSON> said he saw no irony in this. `` We were the liberators of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` We did what we had to do.''
