<HEAD>Inmates Angered Over Columns Missing From Prison Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> has decided to stop publishing stories on legal issues in the prison system's monthly newspaper, angering inmates who say it was the most popular feature in the paper `` Several months ago, they told me there would be no more articles on legal issues generally,'' said <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marble </PERSON>, an inmate who has been editor of The Echo for the past four years. `` That's probably the most-read part of the paper, and it's definitely the part we got the most complaints about if it was n't there. The legal section of the newspaper included a column by the corrections department's staff counsel, articles by inmates discussing recent court decisions and reprints of `` free world'' stories that address penal issues, Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyer </ORGANIZATION> newspaper reported. Corrections department Deputy Director <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> denied Monday that he has banned law-related stories, but said the articles on legal issues often were inaccurate. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said he prefers to devote space to describing prison services available to inmates to prepare them for the real world. `` I'm not going to do any free advertising for lawyers, and I'm not going to teach people how to sue,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said `` But we will do articles on things like the services provided for inmates by the inmate attorney.'' Staff attorney <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON>, whose state-supported office offers legal advice to inmates, said he had completed columns for the May and June issues when word came they would n't be used. <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said a column on the Open Records Act might have displeased a corrections department board member. The legal issues column addressed such subjects as the consequences of filing frivolous appeals and changes in such matters as deadly weapons findings by juries and whether notaries are needed for certain legal documents. Marble said several inmates have indicated they plan to file suit over the format change. `` I get sued every day and I'm sure I'll get sued over this,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` It's part of my job.''
