<HEAD>Quebec Re-elects Liberals; English Speakers Register Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> governing <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> retained its majority over a steady challenge from the separatist <LOCATION> Parti </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quebecois </LOCATION> and a surprising protest vote from the province's English-speaking minority Results of Monday's vote in the largest and second most populous Canadian province showed the Liberals led by Premier <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> with 92 seats in the 125-seat provincial assembly. The <PERSON> Parti </PERSON> <PERSON> Quebecois </PERSON> won 29 seats, a gain of six, and a new <ORGANIZATION> Equality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> captured four in traditional Liberal strongholds. `` I believe that this is a sign of confidence,'' a smiling <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>, whose early hopes for a calm campaign capitalizing on four years of continuing prosperity in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s largest province had been dashed by environmental protests and labor unrest, said at his district headquarters. The Parti Quebecois had been reeling from its provincial election debacle four years ago in which it lost power to <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> and fell to only 23 of the then-122 seat assembly. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Parizeau </PERSON>, who won an internal party battle to put it back on a hard-line course last year, ran a strong campaign on a platform of eventual independence for the majority French-speaking province. `` We have progressed solidly toward the goal that we think is the right one,'' <PERSON> Parizeau </PERSON> said Monday night in reiterating his separatist aims. Supporters chanted `` Le <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> aux Quebecois,'' or `` Quebec for Quebecers.'' The Equality Party was formed by English speakers irate over <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s language policies that still restrict all outdoor signs to French. Supporters at party headquarters sang `` O <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>,'' the national anthem, at their victory celebration. `` I have never been so proud to be a Canadian and a Quebecois in my life,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Libman </PERSON>, 29-year-old architect who formed the <ORGANIZATION> Equality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> just months ago. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>, an economist, counted on Quebecers being more interested in pragmatic issues related to prosperity than to independence. He pointed to a 4 percent annual economic growth rate, the creation of 233,000 new jobs and the social stability that lasted most of his term. But the idea of separatism for <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, thought to have been put to rest in a 1980 referendum in which 60 percent of the voters rebuffed it, held on to its current of support. The Parti Quebecois won 38.7 percent of the popular vote in the December 1985 provincial election. Projections were that it had increased slightly to 40 percent Monday. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>'s support among <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s English-speaking minority, which traditionally had voted Liberal, was hurt by his refusal in December to allow more than a token change in provincial laws restricting commercial signs to the French language. His compromise solution allowed bilingual signs only indoors as long as the French-language portion was significantly larger than the English. <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, which has a population of 6.5 million, is 81 percent French-speaking. Supporters of language restrictions argue they are necessary to protect French and <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>'s special culture surrounded by English elsewhere in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Those who oppose the restrictions say they violate basic rights. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>'s term before the language uproar last winter was unusually quiet as <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> settled into a period of strong economic growth, leading to speculation that the Parti Quebecois could be facing its last days. The separatist party had controlled the provincial government from 1976, at the height of the period when power in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> shifted from the English-speaking minority to the French majority, to their defeat in 1985. Monday's victory confirmed the comeback by <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>, whose colorless style could almost be considered a trademark. He was the youngest premier ever elected in <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> when he won the 1970 election at the age of 36, but the <LOCATION> Parti </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Quebecois </LOCATION> then ousted him six years later at the height of separatist sentiment.
