<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Orders for `` big ticket'' durable goods, boosted by robust automobile sales, rebounded a strong 3.8 percent in August for their steepest advance this year, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said demand for durable goods, items expected to last more than three years, totaled a seasonally adjusted $ 126.7 billion, their biggest increase since a 7.4 percent advance last December. The August advance came after a bigger decline than previously thought in July. July orders fell 2.5 percent rather than the 1.9 percent originally reported. Orders had risen 1.3 percent in June. Durable goods orders, a bellweather of the economy's performance, have bounced up and down throughout the year, rising in March, April, June and August and falling in January, February, May and July Transportation equipment orders were up 6.7 percent to $ 36.3 billion as a large increase in motor vehicles and parts more than offset a decline in aircraft and parts. Transportation orders had risen 1.8 percent in July. Excluding the transportation category, durable goods orders were up 2.7 percent. Orders for non-electrical machinery, including computers and a wide variety of industrial equipment, increased 9.2 percent to $ 22.8 billion after a 10.4 percent decline in July. The closely watched non-defense capital goods sector fell 9.8 percent to $ 37.4 billion. Economists use this category as a barometer of business investment plans. Orders for both electrical machinery and primary metals, including steel, were down last month, the department said. Electrical machinery orders fell 0.9 percent to $ 19.6 billion, with communications equipment showing the largest decrease. Primary metals were off 1.9 percent to $ 11.3 billion. Excluding the defense category, which swings widely from month to month, orders rose 3.9 percent in August after falling 1.5 percent in July. Volatile military orders increased 1.9 percent to $ 7.8 billion after plunging 14.7 percent in July. Shipments of durable goods in August rose a record 9.5 percent to $ 128.4 billion, much of it reflecting automobiles. The previous high during the current seven-year economic expansion was a 4.5 percent increase in January 1983.
</TEXT>
