<FIRST>r a PM-Fusion     09-26 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Institute Fails To Duplicate Results of Fusion Experiments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Experiments at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>'s new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fusion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> have shown no sign of producing fusion, says the director of the research center `` We have a conference coming up here next February,'' said director <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON>. `` If we do n't have any papers to present, then this place will be closing up shop. I'm not saying I will do that. I'm just saying I think that is what would happen.'' The center was set up by the state after chemists <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> announced at the university in March that they had harnessed the energy source that powers the sun by achieving fusion at room temperature in a jar. <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON> said Monday the institute's more than 20 electrochemical cells, all variations of <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON>'s experiment, have produced no excess heat and no fusion products such as neutrons or tritium. `` It's gotten to be time for us to start wondering if we're doing anything wrong,'' said <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON> He called the situation `` unnerving.'' Scientists around the world have had difficulty duplicating <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON>'s experiments, which held out the possibility of a cheap, relatively safe and virtually inexhaustible supply of energy. Conventional nuclear energy, or fission, splits atoms; fusion produces energy by fusing them together. <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON> said the institute is negotiating with the <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Menlo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, for funding. The institute so far has only $ 4.3 million in state money to spend on research. Neither <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kulhammer </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> EPRI </ORGANIZATION> vice president for exploratory research, would say how much money is involved. In another development, a scientist from the European laboratory <ORGANIZATION> CERN </ORGANIZATION> said that a worldwide examination of attempts to duplicate cold fusion shows there is little hope that it is real. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, a self-described student of `` pathological science,'' said that in most cases the experimenters found no effect or found something early on but could n't repeat it. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, a physicist at the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, was in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> last week to visit with <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> scientists. <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fleischmann </PERSON> were in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and are not expected to return until Thursday. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said cold fusion fits the mold of other wrong experiments in scientific history that appeared to hold huge promise. `` It is normal when you have a wonderful dream to accept the positive and suppress the negative,'' he said. `` Everyone does it. Scientists are human, too.'' <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON> said <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> `` gave his talk as if the book has been closed, and I think it's premature.''
</TEXT>
