<HEAD>Lake Liquidated in Bankruptcy Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESHIRE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An entire lake has been liquidated, so to speak, sold to two businessmen for $ 110,000 at a lakeside auction. The bidding for <ORGANIZATION> Hoosac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION>, a 120-year-old reservoir built to provide water power for mills, was part of a bankruptcy proceeding begun eight years ago by the now-defunct <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Print </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>. The sale is subject to court approval. The winning bid in Monday's auction, held on a causeway spanning the 566-acre lake in the <LOCATION> Berkshire </LOCATION> hills of western <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, was entered by <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Shea </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> and <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Loscocco </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shea </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Loscocco </PERSON> own about half a dozen bodies of water in central <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> that are used mainly for recreation. `` We have an interest in water,'' <PERSON> Shea </PERSON> said. `` We have n't really developed anything and we do n't have any plans at this point to do any developing.'' Along with the lake, they get 50 acres on the shore. Some <LOCATION> Cheshire </LOCATION> residents were aprehensive about the sale, fearing that a private owner might charge admission or erect large developments. Some had hoped the auction would flop, proving the lake does n't have commercial potential and possibly opening the door for its donation to the town or state <LOCATION> Cheshire </LOCATION> had been paying $ 750 a year to use the lake. Town officials had said the lake would be a bad buy because of the cost of weeding, expected to be $ 31,000 this year, and because of the age of its dam. The lake was created in the 1860s, when a group of manufacturers bought land and dammed the <LOCATION> Hoosac </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> to produce water power. In 1912 the <ORGANIZATION> Hoosac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reservoir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was formed to oversee management of the water; <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Print </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> was the last remaining shareholder of that company.
