<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defiant Slovenian lawmakers set a vote Wednesday on whether <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s most liberal republic should be allowed to secede, despite warnings that authorities could impose a state of emergency. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the Slovenian <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the federal parliament scheduled emergency sessions today to discuss the political crisis sparked by the proposed amendments to the republic's constitution. Slovenian lawmakers in the federal parliament said they would boycott the <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> session. According to a proposed amendment, <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION> would have a `` lasting and inalienable right to proclaim self-determination, including the right of secession.'' Another proposed amendment declares that Slovenian authorities have the sole right to declare a state of emergency in the region and to authorize the use of Yugoslav army units in the republic. <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, which borders <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, is the most prosperous and westward-looking of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six constituent republics. It has already allowed an unprecedented degree of democratization, including the formation of several independent political parties. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s state and communist party leadership has criticized the amendments as being contrary to the federal constitution. The collective state presidency in charge of the armed forces said Monday it will use all `` legal measures'' to prevent the adoption of the amendments, indicating it might proclaim a state of emergency in the northern republic. <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comm