<HEAD>Carriers to Pay 25 Cents for Misdeliveries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORTHINGTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Letter carriers here have agreed to pay 25 cents out of their own pockets for each misdelivered piece of mail. The bounty will be paid to residents of this <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> suburb who return the wrongly delivered letters. `` We're calling it the Worthington Letter Carriers Money Back Guarantee,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, said today. The 60-day trial program along 11 routes is an outgrowth of a national, voluntary program by the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carriers </ORGANIZATION>. `` We wanted to indicate to our customers that we were concerned about getting their mail delivered to them properly, and we wanted to make sure that we were going to do everything we could in order to do that,'' <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> said a similar program in High Point, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, operated for about a year and paid out $ 26. Under the program, which began Monday, carriers will pay for any misdelivered first-class items that had been properly addressed. Customers will be given a form to fill out and an envelope in which to return the misdelivered mail at no cost. About 3,000 to 5,000 customers will be involved in the project <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> said the the union would pay for misdeliveries by part-time or substitute carriers.
