th for beheading four policemen, also during the uprising. Last year's demonstrations were crushed after a series of bloody army clampdowns in which thousands were killed. The government has used the sporadic violence that occurred during the largely peaceful protests to justify its use of force against dissent, saying the country was on the verge of anarchy. It continues to rule by martial law. Some dissidents have blamed the violence and rumors _ such as those surrounding the poisoning of drinking water _ on government-paid provocateurs. Western diplomats in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> say several thousand pro-democracy activists have been arrested since opposition leaders <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> and Tin Oo were placed under house arrest July 19.
