<ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disabled </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accessible </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, would step up the protest to dispel the notion that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is openly addressing their demands. `` The administration, up to now, was willing to throw us out. If we do n't do something, they'll just let us sit here,'' <PERSON> Auberger </PERSON> said. `` We're going to close it back down again. They need to know our issue is n't going away.'' ADAPT members are demanding that <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> sign an executive order requiring the lifts. They said they also want the administration to implement a 1986 law requiring better disabled access at airports. The protesters say they wont' t move until <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, who visited <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> on Monday for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s convention, signs the <PERSON> Cason </PERSON> said no decision had been made as to whether the protesters would be removed today. `` We'll play it as we go,'' he said. The demonstrators' blockade near the main entrances to the building Monday forced employees and others to leave use an exit on the lower level. ADAPT has also been trying to force the installation of lifts on all new buses through the courts. In <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, a federal appeals panel backed their lawsuit, saying federal law requires lifts on new buses. But in July, the full 3rd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> overturned