 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> today condemned the murder of two <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> civilians in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, calling it a `` cowardly act of terrorism.'' The civilians, whose names have been withheld pending notification of their relatives, were killed in an ambush on a road about 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> shortly before Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> arrived in the country to talk about the future of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases there. The Americans worked for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a contractor at <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> O'Donnell </LOCATION>, a U.S.-run communications facility. The road on which the Americans were attacked runs between the camp and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said in a statement that the civilian contractors of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> `` were murdered in a carefully planned ambush while driving in <LOCATION> Tarlac </LOCATION> province.'' The ambush `` evidently required a certain amount of preparation,'' he said. `` We deplore this senseless and cowardly act of terrorism,'' he said. `` Acts like this will not deter us in our resolve to support the democratic government in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>.'' In the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, local authorities said the Americans' car had been blocked by a dump truck and the jeep. Gunmen jumped out of the jeep, sprayed their car with semi-automatic weapons fire and then opened the car door and fired into the victims' bodies. The military believes the assailants were <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> rebels, who operate in the <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> area, the officials said. <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities have joined local officials in the investigation.
