<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House gave its endorsement today to a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> compromise for funding the war on drugs that would boost the president's plan by $ 900 million. Presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that, while some details of the bipartisan agreement still need to be worked out, the plan `` does appear consistent with our objectives.'' `` We do expect to accept this arrangement and hopefully we can get on with implementing the drug plan,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters. Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, earlier said the agreement is `` not a final solution, but it is a good first step toward fighting the war on drugs `` The <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people wanted more than the president requested, and this gets more,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> told reporters in outlining the plan Monday night. The agreement, subject to final approval by a handful of key senators who were returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> today, would raise to $ 8.8 billion the anti-drug funds for the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. It includes an across-the-board cut of about 0.43 percent in other federal programs to pay for the stepped-up drug war. Senate Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., called the agreement on financing the plan `` fairly final. But he noted disagreements remained on when to take up separate legislation enacting parts of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s anti-crime package, including capital punishment and drug testing for those arrested on drug charges. Sen. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, R-Ore., the chief negotiator for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republicans, said the <ORGANI