<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An East German emissary today told East Germans holed up in the West German Embassy that they can legally emigrate to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> but first must return home, a spokesmen for the refugees said. <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> arrived today to speak to representatives of about 1,200 East Germans who have crowded the garden of the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in hopes of obtaining safe passage to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. After meeting with <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON>, between 50 and 60 East Germans boarded a bus that reportedly took them to a <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> railroad station for their journey back to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The others, however, remained in the embassy quarters and it was unclear if they refused the East German offer. <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> is an <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> lawyer who has close contacts with the East German leadership. Refugees who took part in the negotiations told reporters waiting outside the embassy that <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> gave them a personal guarantee they could emigrate once they returned home. Already, more than 20,000 East Germans have fled to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, which incensed <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leaders when it opened its border to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> on Sept. 11. In <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, dozens of other East Germans arrived Monday outside the closed <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> to seek passage to the West. Some said they swam rivers by night or walked through forests on the Polish-East German border. In <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, a Western reporter on Monday afternoon witnessed some 40 new arrivals scale the 7-foot fence of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> Embassy in the conspicuous absence of Czechoslovak police who had earlier patrolled the street outside, urging reporters to leave. By nightfall, the number of East Germans holed up inside the compound had reached around 980, refugees reported. Some said they'd had to spend Sunday night in the open air for lack of <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> tents, but new tents arrived during the day. In the area near the embassy, police have towed away all East German cars. `` The situation is getting ever more difficult,'' said a 40-year-old East German, who, like all the others, asked for anonymity. He said that his wife and children had successfully made it to the West via <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, but he himself was intercepted by Czechoslovak border guards as he drove in his car toward the Czechoslovak-Hungarian frontier. Other would-be refugees were also caught. Fearing imprisonment at home, he told a reporter, `` Where else should I have gone? The <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> was the last way out.'' Those camping in the embassy garden are mostly people aged 30-40, but there are also 200 children including several infants. There was hardly any space left to put up new tents. In <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, at least 300 East Germans are being accommodated, either in a group of <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> houses in the villa district of <LOCATION> Saska </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kepa </LOCATION> or in a park-surrounded former seminary in <LOCATION> Tarchomin </LOCATION>, just outside <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. The embassy was closed to the public last week to prevent more refugees from entering. The East Germans were anxious to be allowed onto embassy grounds on Monday, but guards stood inside the locked gates. However, embassy officers after making an announcement in the afternoon could be seen escorting small groups away from the embassy, presumably to a shelter for the night. A tall young East German who identified himself as <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, 23, described his escape from his homeland. He said he blew up an air mattress, placed his belongings on it and then swam with the mattress across the <LOCATION> Neisse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> that forms the Polish-East German border in southwest <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.
