<HEAD>Perpich Asks Supreme Court To Review National Guard Lawsuit Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said Tuesday he is asking the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to review an appellate decision upholding a law that stripped governors of their veto power over <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> training missions. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> enacted the law, known as the Montgomery Amendment, after several governors in 1985 and 1986 objected to deployment of <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> personnel on maneuvers in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, where the governors felt there was a danger of involvement in wars. The law `` presents a states' rights issue of historical importance,'' <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` Because of conflicting decisions in the lower courts, this issue warrants a final resolution by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said he has never disapproved of any federal training deployment of the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, but is challenging the law's constitutionality because it invades on a governor's authority <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> initially challenged the Montgomery Amendment on Jan. 28, 1987. The amendment to a 1986 defense bill says governors may not withhold their consent to <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> missions `` because of any objection to the location, purpose, type or schedule of such active duty.'' The amendment was upheld in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, but a three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court