<HEAD>Monastery Vandalized to Protest Auschwitz Convent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vandals damaged the remains of a 13th-century Carmelite monastery in northern <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, apparently to protest a controversial Carmelite convent near the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> death camp in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, an official said Tuesday. <PERSON> Shalom </PERSON> <PERSON> Yankelevitch </PERSON>, commissioner of antiquities for the city of <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION>, said the vandalism followed reports that Jewish religious extremists had threatened Carmelite nuns carrying out an archaeological dig at the monastery. The vandalism was discovered last week. Sister <PERSON> Damien </PERSON>, a Carmelite nun from <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> who is leading the dig, told <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> television her order has always opposed having nuns pray at the Roman Catholic convent on the edge of <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. `` So for people to hurt our ruins here to try to make the sisters come out, they are hurting the people who are trying to get -LRB- the nuns -RRB- out,'' she said. Jewish leaders say the convent, with its 12-foot-high cross, is offensive because of the presence of Christian symbols at a place where 2.5 million Jews were killed by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in World War II. <PERSON> Yankelevitch </PERSON> said the damage to the convent near <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION> came after an article appeared in a local newspaper saying anonymous religious groups demanded the nuns delay their dig until the convent at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> is moved. The vandals caused extensive damage, <PERSON> Yankelevitch </PERSON> said. `` They toppled the entrance arch into the ... cathedral, and the arch leading to the 2nd floor of a sideyard, and stone steps. All this from the 13th century was damaged and broken,'' he said. A group of American archaelogists has been excavating for two years at the one-acre site on biblical <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carmel </LOCATION>. The dig has uncovered new parts of the well-preserved Carmelite cathedral and a fortress and ancient water system that are part of an entire monastery complex. The Carmelite nuns are trying to prove that the site dates back to the 5th century, which would predate by 100 years any other <ORGANIZATION> Christain </ORGANIZATION> order on <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carmel </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carmel </LOCATION> is the spiritual center of Carmelites throughout the world, and Carmelites here have written letters to Israeli newspapers calling for moving the convent from <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. Some have traveled to <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> to press for transferring the nuns. <PERSON> Yankelevitch </PERSON> said he believed there was a connection between the vandalism and threats by religious groups, but he did not rule out other possibilities. The investigation is in police hands, he said. The damage was reported as the controversy over the convent in <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> seemed to be easing. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> said last week that he believed the nuns should be moved to an interfaith prayer center to be built in accordance with a 1987 agreement between Jewish and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> officials. The statement overcame opposition by Polish primate <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON> and Polish Catholics, who have argued the nuns should be allowed to remain because they cause no harm and because many Christians also were killed at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. In the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday canceled an invitation to <PERSON> Glemp </PERSON>, citing what it called his `` harrowing'' anti-Jewish statements. The <ORGANIZATION> Cathol