<HEAD>Sister's Death Brings Men Out of Urban Cave</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ring </PERSON> showed up at his corner grocery, singing `` I'm Just Wild About Harry'' in praise of his favorite cat, it marked his chief contact with the world for the day. His brother, <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>, was never seen at all. It was only when their equally reclusive sister, <PERSON> Marie </PERSON>, died last week that the brothers were delivered from a life in a filthy home without running water or electricity. But now they face an uncertain future. Said <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, a neighbor since the Rings moved to the working-class <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> neighborhood in the 1950s: `` I could n't believe it Who could get by today without electricity and gas and water? ... I would have helped them, but they were n't people who wanted you to get involved.'' <PERSON> Gerri </PERSON> <PERSON> Abban </PERSON>, the cashier at nearby <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>'s Market, says the plight of the Rings was obvious but the best way to help them was not. The market's owner since 1956, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, gave <PERSON> John </PERSON> discounts and looked the other way when one of his checks bounced. But the Rings would not let anyone in the house, and social workers and priests responded to Ms. <PERSON> Abban </PERSON>'s pleas for help by noting that the family had a right to privacy. `` I sold them charcoal in the winter so they could heat the house,'' Ms. <PERSON> Abban </PERSON> said. `` I sold them rubbing alcohol, five bottles at a time, so they could cook. I sold them bottle after bottle of Anacin because they'd get wicked headaches from the smell in the house. Paper plates, paper cups, bottled water. It was unbelievable.'' The isolation ended last week when <PERSON> John </PERSON>, 59, called police to report that his 58-year-old sister's pulse was weak. Police said they arrived to find her dead, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> and 62-year-old <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> in poor mental condition. The brothers refused to leave the house, though it reeked of waste from the Rings and their two dozen cats. They were sent to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> for evaluation, and a hospital spokeswoman would say only that they were in stable condition. In an interview published Tuesday, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ring </PERSON> said neither he, his brother nor his sister had worked since the 1950s or early'60s, choosing instead to live with their parents, who died more than a decade ago. `` The cats took all our money ... cost us $ 60 a week worth of cat food. That's why we could n't fix the place up,'' Ring said. `` But we're going to now.'' Asked why he did n't accept help, <PERSON> Ring </PERSON> said: `` I did n't want to bother anybody. But pretty soon <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> and I will be well again and we'll go back and fix the house up. I'm sure that everything will be fine as soon as we get out of the hospital.'' City officials say however that the house is in such bad shape it has been condemned. And the <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> came for the cats. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, proprietor of <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>'s since 1956, said the Rings did n't have much, but they received some sort of veterans assistance and were n't penniless They paid with personal checks that occasionally bounced, and <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> gave them unofficial discounts. `` I'm not saying how many -LRB- checks bounced -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. `` Let's just say I've got a few in my file.'' `` If <PERSON> John </PERSON> did n't take his medication, he went wild,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. `` When he'd come down to the store to buy, he'd stuff his pockets, he'd throw things around and yell at people. We understood him. We did the best we could. We got him home.'' Neighbors said <PERSON> John </PERSON> and his sister went to church each Sunday. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> recalled <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> as `` a very fine lady, always well-spoken. She seemed to be well-read and her whole life was taking care of her two brothers. It's a mystery to me why, but she did it.'' As for the other brother, `` I do n't know anything about <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. `` I saw the man once in a flashing instant when I went to the house.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ring </PERSON> said his brother had been wounded in World War II. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> gave up trying to understand why the Rings lived the way they did. `` You had a good daddy. I had a good daddy,'' he said. `` We ca n't all be lucky.'' `` Everybody has a right to their privacy. It was my business and it was n't my business. I sent a plumber up there, I sent an electrician, and they could n't get in.'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, a retired union leader, said that he thought <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> had died back in the early 1970s. Then some years ago, a fire broke out on the street, and he saw a man with a beard down to his belt and a blanket around him. `` I said, ` Who is that?' And someone said, ` That's <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>.' I never believed there was -LRB- a third person -RRB- in there.''
