<HEAD>Three Couples Agree to Divvy Up $10,000 Prize in Kissing Contest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT to Tuesday.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three couples have been declared winners in the first annual Great American Kiss-Off, but their lips are sealed about what they'll take home for their efforts. The six contestants agreed to divvy up the $ 10,000 top prize after smooching for 42 days then hiring a lawyer to legally unlock their lips. `` I'm just glad it's over,'' <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON> said Tuesday, one day after all parties embraced the pact. He and his wife, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>, were declared the official first-place finishers after they and two other couples outlasted 11 other pairs who entered the contest sponsored by a furniture company. The company agreed to let the three top couples split the $ 10,000 as they pleased and without revealing how. `` We thought it was going to be a two-week thing, but it turned into a marathon,'' said <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON>. `` I'm recovered now. But it still feels like I'm kissing. ... It's like when you've been wearing a hat for four or five weeks and then take it off. The hat still feels like it's on.'' But <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON>, 39, said he still kissed his 36-year-old wife and mother of their five children good night. `` I'm not tired of kissing her,'' he said. `` I think everyone decided we should be the winners because they realized we could go on the longest.'' <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON>, who is unemployed, said he survived financially because he owned a tile fitting business in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> before moving to <LOCATION> Fernley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, in 1985. <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Cashill </PERSON> said he was hired by parents of the other two couples in their late teens and early 20s to help end the contest so their children could get on with their lives. `` These people were really caught up in a horrible situation,'' <PERSON> Cashill </PERSON> said. `` It was like they were in bondage. They would n't quit; $ 10,000 is a lot of money. Under the agreement, the <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON> couple got the deed to an <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> time-share condominium, which was the first-place prize along with the money. The declared second-place finishers and winners of an expenses-paid trip to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> were <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> and <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Gubler </PERSON> of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bret </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> <PERSON> Block </PERSON> of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> claimed the third-place prize of new living room furniture. The pact to end the Kiss-Off began developing Friday and the contest was suspended pending the outcome of negotiations. <PERSON> Butch </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, a publicist for the Kiss-Off, said the furniture company was a bit disappointed in the outcome of the contest. `` It was fairly anticlimactic,'' <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> said. `` We were hoping there would be a big winner and a ceremony with champagne to hand out the $ 10,000 check.'' <PERSON> Gubler </PERSON> expects to go back to his father's auto body shop, while <PERSON> Watson </PERSON> will resume his career as a financial planner and Ms. <PERSON> Block </PERSON> will look for a new job, having lost hers at a bank, <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> said. Contest organizers thought the competition would last only about two weeks, but relatively easy rules allowed the contest to continue. Couples had to kiss for 12 hours each day, from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m., in the furniture store's parking lot, with five-minute breaks each hour. On Aug. 26, three competing couples, including the Gublers, married in a triple wedding ceremony.
