<HEAD>Third World Military Spending Needs Scrutiny, Says Conable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Urging closer scrutiny of Third World defense budgets, <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> said Tuesday poor countries spent more on the military than on health and education combined at times during the past decade. `` But let us hope that in the changing political climate of the 1990s, resources are increasingly allocated to more productive purposes,'' he said in an address prepared for the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting. As a whole, low income countries currently spend around 20 percent of their funds on defense, <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> said. Despite cuts in other necessities, `` the $ 200 billion which the developing world spends annually on the military has largely been protected,'' he said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> spent about $ 290 billion on the military in fiscal year 1989, or about 29 percent of the national budget. <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> said it's time for `` developing countries on one side, and their arms suppliers on the other,'' to `` adapt to a world where budgets are tight. `` It is important to place military spending on the same footing as other fiscal decisions, to examine possible trade-offs more systematically, and to explore ways to bring military spending into better balance with development priorities,'' he said. Every country has the right and duty to defend itself, and `` in evaluating military expenditures governments should be realistic, but they also should remember the human consequences of these choices,'' said <PERSON> Conable </PERSON>, who as a former <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Congressman had some experience with guns-vs. - Military spending is `` a sensitive component of the fiscal problem'' that can no longer be neglected, <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> said, because arms are often a prime source of external debt, accounting for a third or more of the interest due by some major Third World debt-ridden countries.
