 The slain father of track star <PERSON> Zola </PERSON> <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> said in his will that his three daughters were not welcome at his funeral, which was scheduled for Wednesday, the independent <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>, who had been estranged from his family for several years, was fatally shot Thursday at a farmhouse outside the central city of <LOCATION> Bloemfontein </LOCATION> where he lived alone. A man doing construction work on the farm is being held in connection with the killing. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>'s fomer wife, <PERSON> Tossie </PERSON>, and their son, Quintus, were expected to be at the funeral, but it was not known if Ms. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> and her sisters would attend, according to the news agency. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>, 59, did not attend Ms. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>'s April 15 wedding in <LOCATION> Bloemfontein </LOCATION>, saying he was not invited. Ms. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> left <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1984 and was hurriedly granted a British passport so she could compete in the Summer Olympics in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is barred from the Olympics and most international competition because of its apartheid policies of racial segregation. In the 3,000-meter run, the barefoot Ms. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> collided with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> star <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Decker </PERSON> <PERSON> Slaney </PERSON>, and the American was unable to continue. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON> finished seventh amid a chorus of boos. She later set several world distance running records while living and training in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. But she was constantly dogged by anti-apartheid activists who said she should not be allowed to compete due to her South African connections. Ms. <PERSON> Budd </PERSON>, 23, returned to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in May 1988 suffering from what doctors said was `` complete mental exhaustion.'' She says she plans to forego international competition and live in her homeland indefinitely.
