<HEAD>Pierce's Lawyer Bars Cameras from Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pierce-HUD, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Television coverage, radio equipment and newspaper cameras were barred from former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s confrontation with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday _ a ban forced by his lawyer against what he charged was the panel's `` circus-like atmosphere.'' `` We pulled the plug from their main act because, in fact, we thought it would create a more somber forum,'' attorney <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perito </PERSON> said. `` The circus-like atmosphere has been created by them, not by us,'' <PERSON> Perito </PERSON> said before television cameras assembled outside the congressional hearing where <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> appeared under subpoena. With the cameras gone, <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> invoked his constitutional right against self-incrimination and refused to answer the subcommittee's questions <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s lawyer invoked a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rule that dates to the <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> hearings of the 1950s. It allows witnesses subpoenaed to appear before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to bar broadcast coverage and still photographs of their appearance. Four television networks _ <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> _ failed in their attempt to win a temporary injunction from a federal judge in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday to prevent <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> from invoking the rule. Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Government Operations subcommittee on employment and housing, which is probing <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s tenure as secretary of housing and urban development, said he favored repealing the rule and was reluctantly enforcing it <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON> permitted full coverage of the subcommittee by radio, television and photographers for an hour and 15 minutes while he and other members discussed their investigation and <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s likely refusal to testify. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> did not enter the committee room, however, until after <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON> called a brief recess and ordered television, radio and still photographic coverage to cease. Three television cameras remained in the room, apparently shut off with their lenses pointing away from <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON> then appealed to <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> a final time to reconsider the ban on coverage. `` On advice of my counsel, I ask that the rule be employed,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said. Reporters remained in the room, however, and artists for the television networks sketched the scene. <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON> permitted reporters to use tape recorders to record <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s words. The subcommittee staff asked reporters who recorded the event to sign a brief statement saying the audio recording `` will not be broadcast in any manner.'' The document said reporters agreed `` under the penalty of perjury.'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> read a brief statement saying he would not answer questions, then invoked his constitutional right each time as <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON> posed eight questions. After <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> left, camras and microphones were allowed to record subcommittee members' criticism of the former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> is under subpoena to appear again Oct. 27. <PERSON> Perito </PERSON> said he would decide then whether he will seek to ban coverage again.
