<HEAD>Students Back in Class after Boycott Over Naming School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most students ended a two-week boycott of <ORGANIZATION> Motley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday after school officials and a black parents group settled a dispute over naming the school for civil rights leader <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lowndes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Lowndes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colored </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> agreed Monday to accept a compromise reached during an eight-hour negotiation Sunday with members of the county school board. The compromise came after two days of meetings that mediator <PERSON> Wil </PERSON> <PERSON> Colom </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> attorney, said showed `` real leadership in solving an emotional dispute.'' Under the compromise, the school will be known officially as West Lowndes Elementary, but the building itself will be named after King. `` This retains the board's position on naming a school after the area in which it is located,'' the compromise said. `` Other buildings at any school site can also be named for individuals who are deceased and whose names will not inflame the community,'' it added. The old school name of <PERSON> Motley </PERSON> reflected the name of the local unincorporated community, but blacks protested that the community was named for the family that owned a plantation in the area in slave-holding times. Tuesday's attendance at the elementary school was 350 out of 425 pupils expected, officials said. Only 32 students attended Sept. 12, the first day of school, because of dissatisfaction over the school's name and its incomplete construction. There were 212 students at the school Monday, officials reported. The compromise also says that when the board selects a new assistant superintendent of education, primary consideration will be given to a candidate's ability to communicate with and work with minority students, parents and staff. The <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lowndes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> had wanted a black assistant superintendent. The deal still needs federal court approval under a 1970 court desegregation order. School board approval came in a 45-minute closed session Monday. Board President <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Chism </PERSON> would n't give the vote tally or answer any questions.
