<SECOND>AM-Older Graduates,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds Payoffs for Women Who Return to School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Women who return to college and earn degrees report increased self-esteem and more satisfying jobs, according to a national study released Tuesday. The survey of nearly 3,400 selected graduates from 33 women's colleges also found that 56 percent continued their formal education beyond an undergraduate degree The study, conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, a project of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION>, found that the typical graduate among those studied returned to school in her mid-30s and was married with school-age children. Of those who were married, 55 percent had been aged 18 to 21, the traditional college years, when they wed. The survey, conducted last year, included women who entered college after age 23 and graduated in the years 1970 to 1988. Eighty-eight percent of the women reported that their jobs changed in positive ways after they graduated; 87 percent said their education had contributed to an appreciation of their abilities. `` Achieving that degree had a major impact on their self-confidence, their sense of self-esteem and personal fulfillment and their sense of being an independent person,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> of the College of Notre Dame of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, the principal researcher on the study. Fifty-seven percent of the respondents said their main reason for returning to school was for personal fulfillment; 33 percent cited career reasons. Some 50 percent of the graduates were aged 31 to 44; the oldest was 85. The women typically were first-generation college graduates, had previously earned less than one year of college credit and completed their degrees in four years.
</TEXT>
