<HEAD>Meredith Takes Job on Helms' Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 2 pvs, A senior, with 4 grafs Meredith comment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>, the black man who cracked the color barrier at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> 27 years ago, has been hired to what some see as an unlikely post: adviser to conservative Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>. <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON> said in an interview Tuesday that he had been hired officially on Sept. 5 to advise the senator on questions of race, education, drugs and urban problems, after providing informal advice for the last year. <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>, 58, has changed his views markedly since becoming the first black enrolled at Ole Miss in 1962. Since then, he has called integration the `` biggest con job ever pulled on anybody.'' `` My understanding of the senator's position ... is that every citizen has the entitlement to every right,'' he said Tuesday. `` So there's no need for any specific rights. And I agree with that. `` It is the specific intent of the liberal elite to establish on a permanent basis a dual citizenship in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. They need to keep blacks in a non full-citizenship status. It's not Senator <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> who does n't want blacks to be free in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. It's the liberal agenda. In a letter to acquaintances, he wrote that <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, who is up for re-election next year, `` wants to provide the best possible representation to them as well as the entire black population.'' Some civil rights leader were nonetheless astonished at <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>'s decision to join <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>' staff. `` It's somewhat of a shock to me,'' said <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>. `` I've watched -LRB- <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>'s -RRB- progression _ or maybe I should say retrogression _ from being a militant civil rights advocate to another stand altogether. But I did n't know he had changed to the point he would fit in with Sen. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>' staff.'' `` Without question, Senator <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> has one of the worst civil rights voting records in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Neas </PERSON> of the Washington-based Leadership Conference on Civil Rights. `` For years he has led the right-wing opposition to effective civil rights laws and remedies. He is a senator markedly out of step with the bipartisan consensus on civil rights in this country.'' While <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON> was battling segregation in the South during the'60s, the conservative <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> was gaining a following as a <ORGANIZATION> Raleigh </ORGANIZATION> television editorialist who harshly criticized the movement to bring about racial change. Since his election to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1972, <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> has vigorously opposed civil rights bills and other domestic programs favored by many blacks. He has defended the white minority government of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, fought making <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s birthday a national holiday and criticized such national black leaders as <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON> entered the all-white <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> after spending nine years in the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. His arrival on campus caused rioting; two people died, and President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> sent in troops and federal marshals. Since then, <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>, who was wounded during a freedom march in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> in 1965, has held numerous jobs in various parts of the country, most recently living in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, where he worked as a financial planner and tree farmer.
