<FIRST>u w AM-US-SovietArmsControl     09-26 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Arms Control,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Stress Ending Chemical Weapons Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-UN Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, while accepting a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> call to slash chemical weapons stockpiles, insisted Tuesday on a different approach keyed to halting production of the deadly arms. A cessation of further output of poison gas must be `` part of the parcel,'' senior <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> negotiator <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> said. Even so, the White House welcomed Soviet acceptance of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s initiative. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` I am very pleased with the way things are going. ... We've got some good common ground that I do n't think we had before.'' And <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s press secretary, <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, said the Soviet response `` shows that we are on the same wavelength. It was a very constructive response. Our ultimate objective is total elimination of chemical weapons. And it appears that both nations are now ready to act.'' The Soviet position was outlined by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and then by <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> at a news conference. The two sides disagreed on whether the Soviet plan went beyond <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s initiative. But the two approaches clearly differed in two significant ways. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would have the superpowers retain 2 percent of their chemical weapons until all nations `` capable of building chemical weapons'' sign an international ban. And, as the president explained his proposal Monday in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would keep producing new, binary weapons while destroying older stocks. Binary weapons are deadly, but only when they are mixed. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s move and said, `` The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, together with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, is ready to go further.'' He called for a cessation of production. At a news conference later, Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> said Soviet acceptance was conditional on a halt to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production of binary weapons. `` It is part of the parcel,'' said <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON>, the highest-ranked arms control expert in the Soviet hierarchy. `` It will not be sufficient to get rid of old weapons if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is going to produce new ones.'' A second key difference between the two sides centers on when all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet chemical weapons would be destroyed. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was ready to destroy 98 percent of its weapons in the first eight years of an agreement with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The remaining 2 percent would be retained until 40 nations now negotiating in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreed on a treaty to ban chemical weapons _ and all nations with the capability to produce them signed the pact. This would mean an outright ban depended on the approval of such nations as <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, and possibly <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, which the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration says is on the verge of production. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> have been accused of using poison gas in their Persian Gulf War that ended last year. <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> said the Soviets were willing to destroy all their chemical weapons once the treaty was completed. `` We would n't bar the treaty entering into force if there is one nation capable of producing chemical weapons,'' he said. <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> said the Soviets were not helping any country to manufacture chemical weapons. He placed the Soviet arsenal at 50,000 tons. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials have declined to divulge the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> total. The general assumption is that it is about 30,000 tons. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> also called on the two superpowers to `` renounce the use of chemical weapons under any circumstances.'' And, the Soviet foreign minister said, they should employ `` rigorous verification of the cessation of production of chemical warfare agents.' <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> agreed last week in talks in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hole </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, on a two-step plan for exchanging information about chemical weapons and for trial inspections of stockpiles. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> had a seven-minute meeting with <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> after the foreign minister delivered his speech. He told reporters he had to study the Soviet chemical weapons proposal and that it did not appear to go beyond <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s initiative. But <PERSON> Karpov </PERSON> said `` our proposal is a wider one.'' He said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> was ready to begin negotiations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to reduce stockpiles on both sides. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, in his speech, welcomed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s initiative and said `` we share the desire to rid mankind of these barbaric weapons.''
