<HEAD>Bus Operators Say Service Could Be Cut Because Of Law For Disabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Operators of private bus companies complained Tuesday before a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that the proposed Americans With Disabilities Act could force them to cut service, especially to the poor and rural dwellers. Most of the testimony centered on the requirements under the proposed legislation that inter-city bus fleets be made accessible to the disabled within six or seven years of enactment. The bus operators interpret that requirement as a mandate that all buses be equipped with wheelchair lifts, which they say cost from $ 10,000 to $ 35,000 per bus to install, not to mention maintenance costs. `` The mandatory lift requirement, with its attendant costs, including installation, seat loss, and possible package express loss, would spell the end of intercity bus service in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The operators are proposing alternatives, such as a system of leasing equipped buses or having a limited number in the fleet, making those buses available on call. Advocates for the disabled say they have the same right to spontaneous travel that others have, and a reservations system or other limited availability would prevent that. With 200,000 buses in the total fleet operated by members of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the cost of installing lifts would would range from $ 20 million to $ 70 million, said <PERSON> Henry </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Wilkes-Barre </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION>. He told the surface transportation subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> that by contrast, the industry had operating income of $ 41.5 million from 1982-1986. The bus operators say the installation of wheelchair lifts would result in the loss of up to four revenue-producing seats, not to mention cargo and luggage space and modifying restrooms. Owners also testified that where wheelchair access was in place, demand was minimal. Advocates for the disabled told the subcommittee, however, that the bill does not specify wheelchair lifts, but added that the lift technology is so advanced that the cost estimates given by the industry are exaggerated. Most of the testimony Tuesday and in a hearing by the subcommittee last week dealt with the costs of lifts. A German-designed lift used on <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> buses costs $ 11,000, removes only one seat and occupies no baggage space, said <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Golden </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Disability </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> and Defense Fund. She also said there is no requirement to modify restrooms, adding that the disabled have had long experience coping without bathrooms. She and several other witnesses disputed the claims of low ridership, saying the disabled have been conditioned not be be able to expect to travel. `` It takes time for them to believe the word ` Yes','' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Winski </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> with Disabilities.
