<TEXT>
 Colombian President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>, facing escalating violence by drug lords in his country, will meet with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at the White House on Thursday evening. Barco will stop in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on his way to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to address the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, White House press Secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Tuesday The visit comes as bombings and violence continue to rock the drug-trafficking plagued <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nation, in the wake of <ORGANIZATION> Barco </ORGANIZATION>'s crackdown to rid <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> of drugs. On Monday and Tuesday, three explosions, attributed to drug traffickers, blasted <LOCATION> Cartagena </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>, killing two people. Asked if <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would press Barco to request help from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops, beyond the military equipment the administration already is sending, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said no. `` We have said from the beginning we would respond only to requests by the president. We respect his rights and wishes as president of that country, and whether or not he requests any more aid in terms of money or troops or whatever is entirely within his purview,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The recent bombings, the spokesman said, `` are an exclamation point to the danger there and to the desperation that the country faces in terms of its drug problem. It strengthens the commitment of everyone to continue the fight.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has repeatedly expressed verbal support for <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>'s efforts against the drug traffickers and recently ordered $ 65 million in military equipment and weaponry be sent to assist him. He also has requested $ 251 million from <ORGANIZATION> 