<HEAD>Propose Larger Aid Plan for Poland, Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 24 nations pooling aid for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> agreed Tuesday on the urgency of introducing more measures to support political and economic reforms in the two East-bloc countries. In a final communique at the end of a one-day meeting, senior officials from the 24 donor nations also urged <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to reach agreements with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> to reschedule their foreign debts. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s foreign debt is about $ 18 billion _ the highest per capita in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s foreign debt is a debilitating $ 39 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s executive commission, which is coordinating the aid efforts _ has said rescheduling debts is outside its mandate. The communique noted that $ 271 million worth of food aid has been pledged by the 24 nations to be delivered to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. It was the second meeting by the 24 nations with another scheduled for November. European Community officials put a $ 648 million price tag on the new aid plan with half to be financed by the 12 <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> member states and the remainder by the 12 other donor nations. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation, which did not announce any new measures to add to the $ 169 million already pledged, indicated it could find additional funds and said the $ 648 million should be seen as a minimum amount, not a ceiling. By the end of the meeting $ 133 million was promised by <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> proposed paying $ 216 million from its 1990 budget toward the new plan and suggested the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>'s 12 members could provide $ 108 million more on a bilateral basis. The other donors also would supply $ 324 million. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> executive commission, and <PERSON> Frans </PERSON> <PERSON> Andriessen </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> external relations commisisoner, issued a statement calling the process of political reform and economic liberalization in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> `` still very fragile.'' They said Poles and Hungarians `` could well find their new freedoms threatened by economic disorders.'' `` It would be unthinkable to allow such disorders, which could be alleviated through rapid action, to undermine the prospects for change in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' they added. Following are major provisions of the five-point air program proposed Tuesday: _ To supply such goods as pesticides and farm machinery in addition to food being sent to the Polish government. The food is to be shipped free on condition the government uses the money from sales to improve the private farm sector. _ To improve market access for Polish and Hungarian goods by eliminating quantitative restrictions on their exports and offering trade concessions. _ To grant both countries loans from the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and include them in loan operations usually reserved for developing nations. _ To provide professional training including banking and customs to prepare <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> for market-oriented economies. _ Cooperation to clean up industrialized areas and preserve historical and cultural sites in both countries. <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> participitation in the plan requires approval by the 12 governments and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. The other donor nations that also must approve the proposals are the six members of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, along with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>.
