<FIRST>r a AM-Shelter-FoodStamps     09-26 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shelter-Food Stamps,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Stay In Shelter Can't Jeopardize Food Stamps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A brief stay in a battered women's shelter ca n't jeopardize food stamp benefits, a federal judge ruled. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLaughlin </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> violated its own regulations when it directed a cutoff of food stamps for two women this year after they left shelters for battered women. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said payments by the state to battered women's shelters had to be considered income when calculating the food stamp eligibility of individual women who use the shelters. But <PERSON> MacLaughlin </PERSON> ruled Monday that the state's per-day payments to 16 shelters around the state should be considered emergency assistance, not a substitute for the shelter costs that are part of a family's welfare grant. `` A battered woman does not come to a shelter to find housing,'' he wrote. `` She comes because she needs protection from imminent physical danger and help in ending an abusive relationship.'' The judge said fewer than half of the women who seek shelter can be accommodated by existing facilities and the average stay is only 13 days. He gave the federal government and the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> 60 days to come up with a plan for giving back to welfare recipients the food stamps that were wrongfully withheld from them while the policy was in effect, from Aug. 1, 1988, to April 1 of this year. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, an attorney with <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Mankato </LOCATION>, sued on behalf of the two women from that southern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> city of about 29,000 people. He said the lawsuit was a class action involving about 2,000 women and children in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> who were hurt by the policy. The ruling requires they be identified and reimbursed, he said. For one of the <LOCATION> Mankato </LOCATION> women, the amount was $ 250; for the other, $ 124, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. `` While we may not look at the amount as especially significant, to these women it may mean survival,'' said Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> said the state agreed with <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>' position that the shelter services should not be considered income but was forced to go along with the federal interpretation or face sanctions `` There was more at stake here besides benefits,'' said <PERSON> Loretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON>, director of legal advocacy for the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Coalition for Battered Women. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> said the federal policy had the `` absurd result'' of forcing women to choose between getting their children out of an unsafe home or feeding them. Some women were not going into shelters, or were leaving shortly after getting into them, because they could not afford to go without food stamps, she said.
</TEXT>
