<SECOND>AM-Schools-Cholesterol,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Sets Fat Content Standards For Lunches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> law sets a limit on the amount of fat allowed in school lunches and was the result of a lawmaker's shock at the quality of food served at a school in her district. The law, which goes into effect Jan. 1, requires the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> to set fat and cholesterol levels for all school lunches, and orders the board to force the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s 1,000-plus school districts to follow the standards. The legislation is aimed at high-fat, low-food-value lunches that often serve as the sole source of a child's daily nourishment. The bill was signed last week by the governor. `` I'm sad to say that for many children, the school lunch they eat is the most balanced meal they receive all day,'' said <PERSON> Assemblywoman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Speier </PERSON>, author of the law. `` This is particularly alarming when that lunch consists of a corn dog and tater tots.'' A group called The <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, has issued a report that says the federal government supplies about a third of the food used in more than 24 million lunches served daily at 91,000 schools. The foods include high-fat content items such as ground beef, pork, luncheon meat, ham, butter, cheese and eggs. Health authorities generally agree that the daily fat intake for school children should be no more than 30 percent of total calories.
