<HEAD>Chemical Weapons Will Be Hard to Ban in Middle East</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Arms Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTY KUFUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli officials on Tuesday welcomed President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal to eliminate chemical weapons, but experts suggested the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> would pose a major problem area for putting the plan into effect. <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON>, a spokesman for Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> backed the call for wiping out stockpiles but declined to comment on the possibility of doing so within 10 years as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed. `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> supports very much the banning of all chemical weapons,'' he said. `` We have warned many times that <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> countries are arming themselves with such weapons and have in some cases used them against civilian populations.'' <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON> noted <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> used chemical weapons during the 8-year <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> conflict and reports also surfaced of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> manufacturing them. A <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said, `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s position is that we are totally against stocking or using chemical weapons and any action that leads to the suppression of chemical arms is welcomed and supported by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` We hope that there will be a worldwide movement so that all these weapons will be destroyed and never put to use again.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed Monday that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> would eliminate all of its chemical arms within 10 years if the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and other countries do the same. Israeli military analyst <PERSON> Aharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Levran </PERSON>, a retired army brigadier general, said <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> countries probably would balk at giving up chemical weapons that they saw as a counter to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s reported nuclear capability. He also suggested <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> countries may attach political conditions, such as <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> withdrawal from lands captured in war with <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has never confirmed it, but foreign reports say <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has nuclear and chemical weapons as well as long-range missiles capable of delivering them. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is considering nationwide deployment of protective masks to counter the eventuality of chemical weapons. Civil defense authorities are conducting a yearlong trial in which 3,000 residents of two towns were given such masks. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers have been equipped with modern, protective masks and suits as well as detection and decontamination equipment. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is known to have chemical weapons, including mustard gas and the nerve agent <PERSON> Sarin </PERSON>. It used mustard gas against enemy soldiers while fighting <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and against civilians in <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION>, according to an assessment by <PERSON> Levran </PERSON> and members of an Israeli research group. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> has extensive stockpiles of chemical weapons, including the nerve gas <LOCATION> Sarin </LOCATION>, the report said. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> also is believed to have poison gas. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> also has stockpiles of poison gas, according to the report by the <ORGANIZATION> Jaffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Levran </PERSON> said he doubted <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> would heed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s call. `` The Iraqis are afraid that one day the Iranians will amass the forces and overrun them,'' he said.
