<HEAD>FAA Giving Airlines More Time To Develop Drug Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is extending its deadline for air carriers to submit plans for anti-drug programs, including random testing of employees, officials said Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said 22 of 130 carriers using planes capable of carrying more than 30 passengers have failed to submit their plans, orginally due Aug. 18. A federally mandated anti-drug program for the aviation industry takes effect Dec. 18. The new deadline for submitting proposals is Oct. 9, <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. He said just over 100 companies using smaller planes have submitted proposals for implementing the program, which requires employment, post-accident and random drug testing. <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said it is difficult to tell how many of the estimated 3,000 smaller aviation companies might be covered by the law, since it covers only those with more than 50 employees. The agency has sent letters to hundreds of companies warning them that it will take legal action if they fail to meet the Oct. 9 deadline. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> recognizes that since this is a new requirement and involves comprehensive planning and implementation, the airline industry has faced numerous difficult tasks in developing anti-drug plans,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> letters say. Airlines that fail to comply face penalties of up to $ 10,000 for each day their plan has not been submitted. <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said no fines will be assessed until after the new deadline. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has 60 days to approve each company's plan.
