<FIRST>u w AM-CleanAir     09-26 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>President's Supporters Win One</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s clean air bill defeated an attempt Tuesday to make it require auto exhausts cleaner than those now in force in smog-plagued <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The tough provision proposed by Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., was defeated by voice vote in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> environment subcommittee he chairs The subcommittee is considering amendments to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s legislation to clean the skies of ozone, acid rain and airborne toxic chemicals. The outnumbered <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, who is closely allied with environmental organizations, accepted defeat without a roll call, saying he wanted to avoid forcing members to take a public position against stringent automobile controls. <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, promising to return with a compromise that still would toughen <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s auto requirments, said, `` Sometimes you do n't want them on record so they can re-think their position and come around.'' Rep. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lent </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the parent committee and the main GOP sponsor of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> legislation, said <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>'s proposals would have cost consumers an extra $ 500 per car if fully implemented for model year 2000. For that expense, he said pollution under <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>'s plan would only be cut an additional 2.7 percent compared with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> legislation. Estimates of the cost of current auto emissions contols have clustered around $ 1,500 per car in recent years. Lent said the technology does n't exist to meet the <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> standards, which he said represented `` the dreams of the authors and have no basis in technological fact.'' Whatever happens in the subcommittee, the battle over auto standards is expected to surface again in the full <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has not yet begun work on clean air legislation. Motor vehicles are a major contributor to ozone pollution, in some areas the principal contributor, through the emission of unburned fuel vapors. They also emit oxides of nitrogen and carbon monoxide Ozone, the prime ingredient of smog, is produced by the reaction of hydrocarbons _ unburned fuel _ and nitrogen oxides in the presence of sunlight and heat. Because of its ozone problems, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has tougher auto pollution standards than the rest of the nation. <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>'s plan would have limited hydrocarbon emissions to 0.25 grams per mile _ the standard for <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> starting in 1995 _ from 1993 through 1999, and 0.125 grams per mile after that. Outside <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, cars are limited to 0.41 grams per mile under current law. Nitrogen oxides, which also contribute to acid rain, would have been capped at 0.4 grams per mile from 1993 through 1999, down from 1 gram now, and 0.2 grams after 1999. <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>'s proposed limit for carbon monoxide was 3.4 grams per mile from 1992 through 1999, the current standard, and 1.7 grams afterwards. The administration's proposed standard for hydrocarbons is 0.25 grams per mile by 1998; for nitrogen oxides, 0.7 grams by the same year; and for carbon monoxide, retention of the current 3.4 gram limit. Rep. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Walgren </PERSON>, D-Pa., who supported <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, said, `` We are really in the dark Our eyes glaze over at these numbers.''
</TEXT>
