 Federal investigators looking into the crash of a <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> jet said Tuesday that almost all the tread on the front tires was gone, but there was no indication the wheels had jammed. The finding about the front wheels would be consistent with the pilot's statements that he had tried o bring the jet to a halt before it skidded off the runway into the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> on Sept. 20, said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. Two people were killed and 59 others were rescued from the water after the pilot aborted takeoff of Flight 5050 at <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Although 95 percent of the tread on the front tires was gone, the main landing gear under the wings looked normal, <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> said. The wing flaps were all in normal takeoff position. Investigators reported earlier that the front wheels were locked sharply to the right, indicating that the pilot had turned the tiller to counteract a drift to the left. Capt. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> told investigators that he aborted the takeoff because the aircraft was moving left and he felt and heard a strange vibration. Investigators planned to look inside the engines of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737-400 for additional clues to the cause of the crash. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Santucci </PERSON>, district attorney for the borough of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, who has launched a grand jury investigation of the pilots' conduct, said Monday that urine samples taken two days after the accident contained no sign of drug or alcohol use by the pilot or copilot of Flight 5050. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> and his copilot, <PERSON> Constantine </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleissas </PERSON>, were criticized by federal officials for failing to submit to testing immediately after the crash, although they are not legally required to do so. Medical experts said alcohol would usually not show up in urine samples taken two days after ingestion, although drugs such as marijuana or cocaine probably would.
