<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> is n't the only writer living in an Islamic community who faces threats, intimidation and de facto censorship, the <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION> international writers association said Tuesday. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Blokh </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> PEN </ORGANIZATION>'s international secretary, said a writer with an Islamic background `` can be in a very free city ... and yet he lives in a very permanent state of terror, discreet terror.'' The association, holding its world congress in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, recommended its member chapters invite writers from the Islamic community to discuss such situations, their causes and the means to find a solution. `` We would ask them to come and very discreetly tell us their story if they want to,'' <PERSON> Blokh </PERSON> said at a news conference. <PERSON> Blokh </PERSON> said PEN learned about such cases in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> as it prepared protests of the death sentence by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> over the bestselling novel `` The Satanic Verses,'' which sent <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> into hiding. The late <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> ordered <PERSON> Rushie </PERSON>'s death in February, saying Islam was slandered by the book. He said he also knew of one similar case of pressuring a writer in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` I'm not going to tell you any concrete cases because they are still quite secret,'' <PERSON> Blokh </PERSON> said. He said only the <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> case was known to have `` official status,'' issued by a government, but other incidents of `` religious fanaticism'' could be considered a new threat to freedom of expression that had not been anticipated at the end of the 20th century. The known cases consist of `` pressures, intimidation, sometimes direct threats'' against Islamic writers in English and French, <PERSON> Blokh </PERSON> said. He said the new form of censorship discovered only recently was `` something for which we're not prepared.'' The threats were coming not from a government but from a `` very hard to define'' community, he said. The recommendation on intolerance and fanaticism, as translated by The AP from a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> copy, said the <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> incident `` is not isolated and revealed many other pressures, happily less grave'' on writers that may stem from diplomatic, family, community, religious or terrorist sources. The PEN conference moves Wednesday to <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> before concluding Friday. It is the association's first meeting in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> since a heavily publicized 1986 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> event. PEN, founded in 1921, has 11,000 members in more than 60 chapters organized along language lines. It is an international association of poets, playrights, editors, essayists and novelists.
