<HEAD>Soviet Envoy Warns Movements Against Terrorism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> on Tuesday condemned violence by national movements and liberation struggles and said noble ends do not justify violent means. He did not praise the Palestinian struggle against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation of captured <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> lands in his speech to the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, and the message to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and other movements was unmistakable: `` Freedom must not be sought at the expense of others. `` No support or sympathy should be extended to the so-called movements that allow actions humiliating other nations, or use terrorist, barbaric and inhuman methods in waging their struggle.'' It was the most explicit renunciation yet of violence by groups which <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has supported in the past _ from those in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. `` The time has come finally to realize that not all means are good for attaining even the most noble ends ... The international community condemns and outlaws terrorism. `` We need equally determined action against any kind of violence, whatever the motives or excuses for it,'' he said. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> did not discuss specific conflicts, but emphasized the importance of international cooperation and moral behavior by all nations and groups. He addressed condemnation of violence in his speech even before disarmament and acceptance of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s call to slash chemical weapons stockpiles. Diplomats said it signified a greater Soviet commitment to live up to its words about norms of international civilized behavior and common human values. They also cited Soviet desire to improve relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and to seek a comprehensive settlement in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. `` Violence by the state against its own people must be ruled out altogether,'' <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said. `` Violence on national, ethnic or religious grounds must no longer be tolerated. `` We advocate freedom of choice. `` However, we reject its interpretation as a license to use any means, to commit any violence or to shed blood.'' <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> admitted <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> was disappointed by the setback of the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, but said, `` We are in no way prejudiced'' against the new government, led by non-communists. `` We wish it every success and are ready to cooperate with it.... We see nothing threatening in the fact that a coalition government has been formed in accordance with the will of the Polish people. He said that if tolerance `` is mandatory for us in our attitude toward the current government of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, why are others so intolerant as regards, say, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>?'' It was a clear reference to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dislike of Cuban Communist leader <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>. In his first address since he became <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s foreign minister last month, <PERSON> Taro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakayama </PERSON> explained the new, activist foreign policy of his government Tuesday, including a greater, non-military role in <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping worldwide. <PERSON> Nakayama </PERSON> also said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> would welcome simultaneous or separate <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> membership for both South and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and said <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> was trying to improve its own relations with <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>. He said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> seeks to improve its relations with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and resolve the issue of the Soviet-occupied Northern Territories. <PERSON> Nakayama </PERSON> said `` recent events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'' disturbed the Japanese, a reference to the violent suppression of a student-led democracy movement in June. But he said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> expects <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s policies of reform and openness to remain unchanged. <PERSON> Nakayama </PERSON> announced that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is prepared to provide $ 600 million from 1990 to 1992 to help the poorest countries in sub-Saharan <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and elsewhere restructure their economies. `` As <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> interacts with the rest of the world more intensively and in a broader spectrum of fields,'' he said, `` it realizes that it must play a more active role in international affairs.''
