<HEAD>Immigration Official Relents; Chinese Student To Be Released on Bond</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with INS official changing his
mind and deciding to grant bond. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Federal Immigration...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An immigration official `` had a change of heart'' Tuesday and decided to release on bond a 27-year-old student from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> who was detained when she arrived seeking asylum, her attorney's office said. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ilchert </PERSON>, regional director of the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, earlier ruled against bond for <PERSON> Hoy </PERSON> <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yi </PERSON> after a doctor reported her to be in good health. But later <PERSON> Ilchert </PERSON> `` had a change of heart,'' said <PERSON> Hoy </PERSON>'s spokesman, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. The regional director is the only person who can approve bond in immigration cases. Federal Immigration Judge <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hornbach </PERSON> suggested the checkup last week after a hearing in which <PERSON> Hoy </PERSON> appeared pale, grimaced and said she was suffering from severe ulcerlike symptoms. <PERSON> Hoy </PERSON> and her fiance, <PERSON> Luo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jian </PERSON> <PERSON> Guang </PERSON>, 32, were taken into custody Aug. 7 when they arrived in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> saying they feared reprisals for anti-government protests if they return to their homeland. Immigration officials have the right to detain asylum-seekers who arrive without visas or to release them on bond. While the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> said it has not taken a position on the asylum request, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has filed a report saying it does not believe the students have proven they have a well-founded fear of persecution if they go back to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Their attorney, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Wong </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </