<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 27,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday Sept. 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>Buying A Car _ A Real Shopping Experience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the beginning there were no sticker prices on windows of new automobiles and the public was confused about prices, so the federal government mandated stickers and people became more confused. These people saw millions of look-alike cars on the highway but they had difficulty finding two in the showroom with identical stickers. That's because cars came with a myriad of options, and the dealer might have added more. Those add-ons added up, and some of them were very peculiar, sufficiently so to befuddle the potential buyer. To the Manufacturers Suggested Retail Price were added charges that included freight, preparation and even advertising. Well, the wary buyer thought, this is the way you do business in cars and who am I to buck the system? But, he continued to wonder, is n't that a bit peculiar? I do n't buy my TVs, ovens, refrigerators or even my house that way. The buyer discovered that many of the options were n't options at all _ they were already on the car. And he discovered there were more to come. After agreeing to buy the car he learned it was n't well equipped for the elements That being so, the salesman advised the buyer to consider the paint and internal protection package, rustproofing and an extended warranty. Is n't it foolish, he was asked, to buy a new car and not protect it? Then came the financing. The customer could finance through the company or he could try for his own. The complications rose. Should he take out a lower cost long-term loan or a higher cost short-term loan? It was enough to confuse a computer, and the insurance was yet to come. What to insure, who to insure, how much to insure? After failing to comprehend his warranty, the buyer had no energy left to read the insurance policy. Having gone through this maze a couple of times, however, the potential car buyer felt a growing sense of mastery. It might have taken a decade or so, but he had caught on to the ways and manners of carmakers and their dealers. Then came below-market interest rates and rebates. Those prices stamped to the car window, confusing to begin with, meant even less now because cars were n't selling for those prices. You had a choice: rebate or low interest. Well, it might have seemed that simple, but when you went to the dealer you found that only certain cars were discounted and those were n't the ones you wanted. And you found that the low, low interest rates did n't apply uniformly. You went home to work it out. Which should I take, rebate or low-interest loan? Which would leave me ahead of the game? Should I finance through my bank or the company? Long-term or short-term? Should I take out credit insurance to cover repayments on the chance I might be injured? Wising to the ways of the marketplace, you loved to see companies get into competition with each other, especially near the end of the selling season, when they had to get rid of the old inventory before introducing new models. Like now. You bided your time, worked out the figures in advance and prepared yourself to pounce on the best deal available. After all, you said, carmakers have already announced price increases for the following year. Well, it's true, they did raise prices, but maybe they did n't mean it One of them, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, already has announced discounts from the higher prices on some of its new model-year cars even before the selling season begins. This has produced a situation in which the new, higher-priced cars might possibly be available at less than the prices pasted on the older, lower-priced cars. Put that in your computer and see what comes out. Right now, some analysts of the automotive industry think that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> will join <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> in discounting, but of course each company will have its own special formula for you to endlessly mix, match and compare at your leisure. Nobody tries to look far into the future of anything economic today, since the footing keeps shifting and distorting the perspective. But you should be aware that if competition intensifies the new terms might have to be revised.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, Sept. 27</NOTE>
