<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-TyMiller Adv13-14   09-26 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Ty Miller, Adv 13-14,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 13-14, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ty Miller of ABC's `Young Riders' Went From Motorcycles to Horses</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ty </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who plays a character called `` The Kid'' on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Young Riders,'' says that although he grew up with horses he was more interested in motorcycles. He's in the saddle every day now for this new Western series about the founding of the Pony Express. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> plays the central character of six young men in the show who sign up to carry the mail from <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joseph </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, in April 1860. The show's original title was `` The Kid.'' `` I ride but I do n't ride very well,'' said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who grew up in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in a family that ran a Christmas tree business. `` We always had horses, but it's like when you have a swimming pool and you spend your time at the beach. I spent more time riding motorcycles than horses. We had 2 -LCB- acres and a stable. The horse I rode is now 26 and ca n't be ridden anymore.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and all the members of the cast were sent to cowboy camp for a quick course in how to stay in the saddle. It was run by <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundin </PERSON>, head wrangler for the series. `` I'm finding you just have to get on a horse and ride and ride,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` It's not a textbook thing. In the pilot we only used stunt men for a few shots. They did the dangerous falls. We did all the flat-out riding.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was more concerned with going to <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, to film in 100-degree weather in his leather costume. His character and co-star <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>'s character, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cody </PERSON>, later to become famous as <PERSON> Buffalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bill </PERSON>, wear buckskin. This is the first Western for <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who appeared as bellhop <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> LLoyd </PERSON> in the final season of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Hotel.'' `` My role on ` Hotel' was pretty limited,'' he said. `` Mostly I stood in the lobby and said, ` Good morning, how are you? May I take your bag?' Those of us who worked in the lobby were n't involved in the main stories.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> acknowledges the `` The Young Riders'' series takes license with the facts for dramatic reasons. `` They keep most of us around the station, more so than would happen in real life,'' he said. `` That's for the sake of the stories. We'll say there is n't a mail pouch to take out. I think the riders spent more time on the road.'' Pony Express riders usually averaged 75 miles, changing horses at relay stations every 10 to 15 miles. Occasionally, a rider was required to ride a longer distance. There were 80 riders to cover 1,966 miles in 10 days. The service ended in October 1861 with the completion of the telegraph from coast to coast. `` Not one rider was killed and only one mail pouch was lost,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. He describes his character in the series this way: `` The Kid is very honest and trustworthy. He's the moral center of the group. He's level-headed, kind of reserved. He does n't act on impulse. He's the natural leader of the riders.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> grew up in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. His mother was an artist and his father ran the Christmas tree business. `` My brother runs the business now,'' he said. `` It's the largest Christmas tree retail business in the country. We sell two million trees a year on 52 lots from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> himself appeared headed for a business career when a girlfriend at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> urged him to audition for a commercial. He went to 40 auditions before he got his first job, a silent part in a commercial for a canned ham. After that he did guest roles on such shows as `` Growing Pains,'' `` Our House,'' `` Valerie'' and `` <PERSON> Macgruder </PERSON> and Loud.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was the last one cast in `` The Young Riders.'' He read for the role five times and it was down to <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and another actor before he was approved. Like `` The Virginian,'' his character has no name. He's known only as `` The Kid.'' `` I'm thinking about what I'll do ... if it comes up that I have to sign my name,'' he said. `` I guess I'll just put down an ` X.'''
</TEXT>
