<TEXT>
 `` Lassus _ Missa Osculetur Me'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Gimell </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The Tallis Scholars, directed by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>. `` Lassus _ Masses and Motets'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Nimbus </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> -RRB- Cathedral Choir, directed by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Darlington </PERSON>. It was after solving the case of the <LOCATION> Bruce-Partington </LOCATION> plans that <PERSON> Sherlock </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> completed his monograph on the Polyphonic Motets of <PERSON> Lassus </PERSON>. Experts, according to Dr. <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, rated it `` the last word upon the subject.'' It's unlikely that <PERSON> Lassus </PERSON>' motets will ever be exhausted. He composed 700 or so, of which only a few dozen have been recorded, in addition to his 60 settings of the Mass, 101 settings of the Magnificat, plus hundreds of madrigals and chansons. Born in 1530, <PERSON> Lassus </PERSON> was perhaps the most popular composer of his time. He not only wrote a lot of music, he wrote well, as two new recordings prove. The choir of <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> offers two Mass settings, three motets and a madrigal. The Missa Venatorum, barely 10 minutes long, shows <PERSON> Lassus </PERSON> at his most economical, the kind of music that might elevate the mind without aggravating the knees. Technically, the <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> choir can not match the Tallis Scholars' professional polish, but it is closer to the sound <PERSON> Lassus </PERSON> would have known The Missa Osculetur Me, recorded by the Tallis Scholars, illustrates <PERSON> Lassus </PERSON>' frequent technique of musical parody. In this case the Mass reworks his own motet set to the opening verses of the Song of Solomon: `` Let him kiss me ...'' The performances are ravishing, which is to say that they are up to the Scholars' usual mark. Is it peevish, then, to complain that the disc holds only 49 minutes of music? Encore, Mr. <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, encore! _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Southside'' -LRB- Mercury -RRB- - <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> The Scottish band <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> lives about as far from its namesake as one can get, but it has ambitions as large as the Lone Star state. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' new album, `` Southside,'' is one of the most promising debuts of 1989. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> shows a remarkable amount of maturity and self-assuredness for such a young band, and what `` Southside'' lacks in originality it makes up in consistent quality. The quartet's sound, like so many other mainstream rockers these days, is rooted in the acoustic guitar of frontwoman <PERSON> Sharleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiteri </PERSON>. But it's augmented by the distinctive blues guitar of <PERSON> Ally </PERSON> <PERSON> McErlane </PERSON> and the sort of throbbing bass that's more common to synthesizer bands. Those ingredients are most evident on `` I Do n't Want a Lover,'' this record's first single. That's not the best song on the album, however. The vote here goes to `` Thrill Has Gone,'' an understated country-flavored tune about the souring of a relationship. At times, McErlane's guitar and the wide open spaces of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' sound bring the state to mind <PERSON> Spiteri </PERSON> also understands well the differences between singing and shouting. Her lyrics travel the traditional terrain of relationships with neither great insight nor embarrassing simplicity. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> sometimes follows the traditional tendency of young bands to show their influences a little too openly. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> obviously listens to <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dylan </PERSON>, since the musical hook of `` Everyday Now'' vividly recalls `` I Shall Be Released.'' And the ringing guitars of `` Fool for Love'' sound a lot like U2. But this record is filled with strong melodies and performances. There are no weak cuts, a track record that would make most young bands _ as well as too many established ones _ envious. _ By <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
