<HEAD>The Artists: A Jeweled Grotto Filled With Memories</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20 of Sept. 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Furey </PERSON> worked night and day covering all surfaces in his apartment with painted cardboard hearts, bow ties, stars and squares; small plaster birds; dried lima beans and peas; clamshells from <LOCATION> Coney </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>; mussel and oyster shells; and pieces of tile and glass. Heartbroken over the death of his wife, <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON>, <PERSON> Furey </PERSON> spent six years creating a memorial for her with mementos he found. Then, with nearly 80,000 objects on every wall, ceiling, cupboard and mirror, he left it all behind. He saw his work as an obsession fulfilled. The <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> sees it now as art unpreserved, and is taking steps to save <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>'s creation. `` I was absolutely astonished when I first saw it,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Head </PERSON> <PERSON> Millstein </PERSON>, the museum's associate curator of painting and sculpture. `` It looked like a jeweled grotto.'' The work was discovered last February after <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, a real-estate developer, bought the building in which <PERSON> Furey </PERSON> had lived. After entering <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>'s apartment, he called the museum. <PERSON> Millstein </PERSON> hurried over. For the last few months, she has been trying to persuade the borough of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> to buy the apartment and preserve it on site. The lath walls and heavy plaster would crumble if removed, she said. She said she will document the work with photographs and a transcript of a lengthy interview with the 83-year-old <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>, once an ironworker on the Golden Gate and the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> bridges. <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>, who moved out of the apartment nearly a year ago after it was broken into twice, and now lives with his son, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Chester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, is amused by all the attention. As for being an artist, he's had no formal training, and the only museum he has ever visited is the American Museum of Natural History. He spent 14 to 18 hours a day on his project from 1982 to 1988, cutting out the cardboard figures of hearts, diamonds and bow ties -LRB- made in honor of his friend Bow Tie <PERSON> George </PERSON> -RRB-, and painting each one in a planned color scheme _ but few people then thought his work art. `` Most people looked at it, but they did n't see it,'' he said. <PERSON> Millstein </PERSON> said most people, including some members of <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>'s family, `` thought he was bananas. But not now. His work is called obsessive or personal art, <PERSON> Millstein </PERSON> said, adding that such art is rarely preserved. `` There's has n't been enough encouragement to save it because you ca n't take it to <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s or <ORGANIZATION> Sotheby </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and sell it,'' she said of the noted auction houses in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` It can be, as a matter of fact, quite ugly. It has more to do with obsession than it does with beauty.'' <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>'s outpouring is in the same vein as <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodia </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Watts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Towers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, made out of concrete, seashells and broken glass; <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Trapani </PERSON>'s complex and decorative furniture, which he made in his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> home after his wife died in 1918; and <PERSON> Korczak </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziolkowski </PERSON>'s 35-year project of carving a <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> mountain in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> into a likeness of <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Crazy </PERSON> <PERSON> Horse </PERSON> _ a work his family has continued since his death in 1982. `` It's a private thing these people are doing. It's outside of the main art world,'' said <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, manager of the Cleveland-based Spaces, a gallery that promotes site-specific art. `` Most of these people do n't consider themselves artists. But they are very creative people. ... You look at their work, and you say, ` Holy smokes!''' <PERSON> Millstein </PERSON> said <PERSON> Furey </PERSON> is `` one of a group of artists who spring up all over the world, compulsively forced at some time in their life to finish a project. They usually have some kind of trauma in their life and they are driven to finish a project. A lot of them are older people who have a last burst of artistic creativity.'' Walking into <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>'s apartment is like stepping into a miniature museum that did n't put any of its collection in storage. The floor is the only bare space. He started in the bathroom, moved to the living room, then the kitchen, then the hallway, he said. He covered doors, both sides. He pasted cutouts around the edges of mirrors, and for ceiling work, he rigged up a scaffold. `` This is not slapdash, you know,'' <PERSON> Furey </PERSON> said. `` I would wake up at two, three, or four o'clock in the morning and start making cutouts. I'd paint them different colors and work for eight, or 10 or 12 hours. Then I'd take a nap in the recliner chair for a couple of hours and start up again.'' On the ceilings, he made rings around the light fixtures of shells, bow tie-shaped cardboard cutouts and cardboard stars. In the hallway, he nailed cement-filled shells to the walls. Some of the shells came from a neighborhood deli. A dining room wallpaper of a Western scene is partly covered with the decoupage. <PERSON> Furey </PERSON> also pasted cows, poodles, chipmunks and monkeys next to the wallpaper horses. Hearts are everywhere. Many are bright red. Many others are black. `` The whole project was more or less to kill time and to get over my grief of losing her,'' <PERSON> Furey </PERSON> said of his wife, who died in 1981. `` I had a lot of time on my hands, not much to do, and I missed her.'' <PERSON> Millstein </PERSON> said the objects represented different parts of <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>'s life, and many were for <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON>. The small birds, for instance, represented the couple's peaceful life together. The two had married during the Depression and moved into the apartment in the mid-1930s. They raised five children there. `` We had a good life together,'' <PERSON> Furey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Furey </PERSON>'s art reveals that it was, <PERSON> Millstein </PERSON> said. `` It's a five-room love story,'' she said.
