<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Roger Whittaker Is a Sales Wonder</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY1 of Sept. 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> is a sales wonder. In 25 years, he has recorded 43 albums and sold 30 million LPs worldwide. One single record alone, `` The Last Farewell'' in 1978, sold 11 million copies. `` It's staggering, astonishing,'' said the 53-year-old <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` I face it as it comes along. It's great to know you can do it. If you think about it, you get a swelled head.'' His top-selling albums in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are `` The Best of <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON>'' and `` All My Best,'' both nearing sales of 1 million. Many of his records are sold through TV marketing, including `` Best Loved Ballads'' and `` All Time Heart-Touching Favorites.'' He has just released for over-the-counter sale another album, `` I'd Fall in Love Tonight,'' produced in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>. It includes country music standards like `` Blue Eyes Crying in the Rain,'' `` There Goes My Everything'' and `` Have I Told You Lately That I Love You.'' The singer-songwriter-guitarist now records for <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> after 19 years and 19 albums with RCA. Singing in three languages _ English, French and <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> _ has widened his appeal. <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> also has gained a larger audience through hawking his albums on TV. Universal Records thinks he's someone who can get consumers to buy records at the retail level rather than just picking up the phone and dialing the number shown on the TV screen. `` We're looking forward to adding to our collection of gold and platinum albums,'' said <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowen </PERSON>, Universal president. <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> is a star in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and various points in between. One <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> record store recently had four different <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> albums and five different compact discs. `` I can go anywhere,'' he said. `` It's a wonderful feeling. I've made 10 tours of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> We did better business on this 10th tour than any one we've done.'' Singing love ballads and not making drastic changes in style have helped him do well, he said. `` I've stayed in the style and never tried to conform to convention. I've sung the kind of songs I write even when out of vogue. Fifteen percent of the record-buying public buy my kind of music. I've stayed faithful to that core of people. `` Every once in a while a song comes along that every one takes to, like ` The Last Farewell,''' he said. He described `` The Last Farewell'' as `` a happy marriage of lyrics and melody.'' `` It was number one in places like <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> where they do n't speak English,'' said <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> `` They still play it in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, so the tune must have a lot to do with its success. The English-speaking nations identified with the chorus, ` For you are beautiful and I love you dearly.' `` The lyrics were emotive to me and I identified with them.'' In his writing and singing, <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> looks for songs that express realism. `` If I can relate to what a person is saying, then I sing it. Like ` Downtown' or ` The Last Farewell.' If it reflects something of my own experience, then I sing it.'' <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, now lives in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. He has a degree in biochemistry from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bangor </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>. `` I did become a biochemist,'' he said. `` But I wanted to go into the entertainment business to get it out of my system. The more I got into it, the more I fought to succeed. `` The less I succeeded, the more I fought,'' he said. `` It became a real mania for me. My father threatened me about getting the right job. When I finally found success, he came around a bit.'' Apart from his recording and concert tours, his TV special, `` <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, a Musical Safari,'' was shown by the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> on cable TV. He is active in efforts to help save <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s black rhino, donating proceeds from program sales at concerts and recording royalties to a trust fund to create sanctuaries for the rhino in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
