<HEAD>Sales Up Based on GM Results, But For How Long?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of North American-made cars and trucks rose 12.7 percent in mid-September, based on a strong showing by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, but at least one analyst wondered how long it could go on. The eight major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers said Monday they sold cars and light trucks at an average daily rate of 37,948 during the Sept. 11-20 period this year, compared with a rate of 33,670 during the same time last year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> buyers propelled the company's truck sales up 46 percent and car sales by 11.2 percent. Combined, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s vehicle sales were up 21.7 percent during the period this year over last year. `` They had incentives that were closing, that had been scheduled to end this week and a lot of dealer incentives,'' said analyst <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The dealer incentives, which manufacturers give to their retailers to use as they please, have helped move cars and trucks, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Meier </PERSON>, general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Ray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> `` I think, finally, they realized that when you put the money in the dealers' pockets, they're going to sell them,'' he said of the cars on his lot. <PERSON> Meier </PERSON> said an inventory of 35 1989 model vehicles on his lot at the beginning of the month had shrunk to eight by Monday. `` They -LRB- dealers -RRB- asked us to give them money so they could sell in their marketplace,'' said <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. `` At least in the first 20 days -LRB- of September -RRB-, they're proving that may have made some sense. `` We're just having a very strong September,'' he said. But <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> and other analysts have said for weeks that the boom that has gone on during the past several sales periods may stem from incentives and reports of price increases on 1990 models that are pushing consumers into buy-now thinking. `` The industry has an above average amount of inventory, there are unprecedented incentives and a whopping price increase for the 1990s,'' <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> said. `` -LRB- Sales -RRB- are going to fall off a cliff in October.'' So far this year, car and truck sales by the eight manufacturers are down 1.5 percent compared to the same 1988 period. A 0.4 percent increase in truck sales was more than offset by a 2.6 percent decline in car sales. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> already have begun offering incentives on their 1990 models, sometimes even before the vehicles officially go on sale. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> is expected to jump into the incentive fray. Dealers have worried that consumers are getting so conditioned to incentives that cars and trucks must have them in order to be attractive. <PERSON> Meier </PERSON> was bullish on the future of the industry. `` The -LRB- 1990 -RRB- price increases are one thing, but when people come out and see what they are getting and with the incentives, there is n't that much different,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said sales of its cars and light trucks were up 3.4 percent in mid-September over last year. Car sales were up 2.6 percent and truck sales rose 4.5 percent. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s vehicle sales were down 0.7 percent. Car and truck sales at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> were up 0.7 percent in mid-September. Car sales were up 2.1 percent and truck sales were down 0.7 percent. For the year, vehicle sales at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> were running 5.9 percent behind last year's pace. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has sold 3.9 percent fewer vehicles than it did through Sept. 20, 1988.
</TEXT>
