<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar plunged on world markets as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its major allies demonstrated determination to push the currency's value lower in a bid to solve <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s trade deficit problems The sell-off began in hectic trading in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and was later matched in <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> markets Monday in what traders described as a rout for the dollar.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Auto sales by the eight major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers soared 12.7 percent in mid-September over last year, with much of the gain due to a 46 percent rise in light truck sales at <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Overall, cars and light trucks sold at an average daily rate of 37,948 in mid-September, compared with a 33,670 vehicle-a-day rate last year, according to reports released Monday. Car sales were up 10.2 percent and truck sales rose 17.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lower interest rates lured buyers back into the existing home market in August when sales rose 3.3 percent to their highest level in six months, a real estate group reported. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that existing single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.44 million units last month, up from July's revised 3.33 million units. Fixed-rate home mortgages have fallen to near 10 percent from a peak of 11.2 percent in March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers were reported close to an agreement that could raise production for the rest of the year after a flurry of private bargaining sessions to break a deadlock in their talks. The <ORGANIZATION> Qatar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified sources Monday as saying the ministers were about to reach an agreement on a higher producion ceiling of 21 million barrels a day to begin on Oct. 1 and run through the end of the year. But an evening meeting where <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> delegates were expected to formalize the plan was abruptly postponed, surprising some ministers who had already gathered. Officials said there were last-minute snags in negotiations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> stock shot higher as the movie and television programmer said it was in active discussions about selling the company, triggering speculation that the suitor was <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION>, which previously had indicated an interest in buying a movie studio, each declined to comment Monday on a report that the electronics giant had offered to buy <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the Atlanta-based soft drink maker that owns 49 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s stock, said it was aware <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> was in discussions and that it would consider whatever recommendation may be made.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said it had made the last major asset sale under a $ 5.5 billion divestiture plan as an investor group led by <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> agreed to buy its <ORGANIZATION> Del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monte </ORGANIZATION> canned food business for $ 1.48 billion. <PERSON> Del </PERSON> <PERSON> Monte </PERSON>'s senior management, <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kikkoman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> also are members of the investor group. <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that proceeds from the sale will bring to approximately $ 4.9 billion the amount of money it has earned from its divestiture program.
</TEXT>
