<HEAD>Britain's Trade Deficit Falls, But Still Wider Than Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade deficit eased to $ 3.69 billion in August from a revised shortfall of $ 3.99 billion the previous month, but it was still the fourth-largest gap ever, the government said Tuesday. The Central Statistical Office said the deficit of the current account, which includes services and overseas investments, was $ 3.20 billion, the third largest ever, but down from July's revised deficit of $ 3.50 billion. The pound and stock prices fell sharply on the news. The government said August's figures, like that of the previous month's, could have been distorted by a three-week strike by dock workers at some British ports which disrupted trade flows this summer. Exports totaled $ 12.04 billion in August, down from $ 12.39 billion in July and up from $ 11.01 billion dollars -RRB- in August 1988. Imports totaled $ 15.72 billion in August, down from $ 16.40 billion in July and up from $ 13.68 billion in August 1988. Since the beginning of 1989, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade balance has been in deficit by $ 26.79 billion, compared with a deficit of $ 20.73 billion a year earlier. The current account has been in deficit by $ 22.33 billion so far this year, compared with a gap of $ 13.74 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
