<HEAD>House Seeks to Regulate Alternative Long-Distance Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lede to delete reference to calling cards. A version
moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is taking aim at alleged price-gouging among a new crop of telephone companies that serve the traveling public. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, on a voice vote Monday, passed a bill that would regulate prices and require extensive disclosure to callers using any of the more than 35 alternative-operator companies which have sprung up in the wake of the 1984 breakup of the Bell System. The bill would require the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to investigate the industry's charges and determine if such companies dominate the market enough to require regulation. A companion bill is pending in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The companies would have to file their prices with the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> within 30 days and, if the commission finds them `` unjust or unreasonable,'' the companies would have to justify the rates, which can be far greater than the fees for similar calls from customers' homes. Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., said the legislation was designed to `` protect consumers from price-gouging'' by `` fast-buck artists'' without jeopardizing the future of the operator services industry One caller told the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> he was charged $ 27.53 for a 27-minute call from a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> hotel to <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> using an AT & amp; T calling card. <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T would have normally charged $ 4.60. The measure also would order the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to extend to the entire operator services industry disclosure requirements imposed on five of the companies in February. There are more than 35 operator services companies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> providing approximately 5 percent of the $ 12 billion market for `` dial-0'' services such as credit card, third party billing and collect calls. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> does not regulate these companies' rates because the commission says they do n't dominate the market. But critics say they do dominate in places, such as schools, hotels and airports, where they often control all long-distance calls.
