<HEAD>Consumer, Labor Groups Announce Opposition to Cut in Capital Gains
Tax</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with comments from news conference
today. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The Republicans say ... A version moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer, labor and government watchdog groups announced today their opposition to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan to cut the capital gains tax, saying it would be a windfall for high-income taxpayers. `` Capital gains proponents are asking Americans to ignore the unjustified financial windfall this tax break will provide to individuals who need it the least,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wertheimer </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cause </ORGANIZATION>, a self-styled citizens lobby involved in government ethics isssues. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is once again hearing the claim that there is nothing wrong with the economy that a tax cut for people with incomes over $ 200,000 wo n't cure,'' said <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Claybrook </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> organization. `` The vote is a critical test of whether the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is truly a representative body _ or whether it is a captive of big money lobbyists and the wealthy,'' she said. That vote could come as early as Wednesday. `` If <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approves of this new tax break, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may find it hard to explain to working people back home why they voted for yet another bargain with high-income taxpayers,'' said a statement by the <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislation </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> group. The groups held a news conference in the Capitol as the battle over the capital gains tax moved to the airwaves, with Republicans and Democrats advertising for popular support on an issue that is dividing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sharply along partisan lines. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to raid the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> by reducing capital gains taxes for the superrich and he wants working Americans to pay for it,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., argues in a television spot produced by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` Why are foreign economies growing faster than the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>? One big reason is taxes,'' says a Republican ad that pictures an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag slipping behind flags from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. `` We have one of the world's highest capital gains taxes,'' it says, while the comparable taxes in those other countries are miniscule. The parties were buying time for the ads in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where the target will be the votes of a few mostly conservative Democrats who could decide the outcome when the House votes. It is the biggest test for the new <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democratic leadership under Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and for a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> strategy that seeks to weaken the majority leadership by courting conservative Democrats. The Republicans say Democrats, by fighting the Bush-supported plan to cut the maximum capital gains rate from 33 percent to 19.6 percent over the next 27 months, are attached to a `` tax and spend'' philosophy. The Democratic alternative would raise marginal tax rates on the wealthy to the same 33 percent paid in the bracket that covers the upper-middle-income. That revenue would then be used to restore tax breaks for Individual Retirement Accounts. The Democratic plan also includes a capital gains cut _ to 28 percent, so it would not cut the marginal rate paid by the most wealthy. `` It's clearly a reconfirmation that they want to raise taxes,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said Monday. `` Who's going to believe they want to stop there?'' <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> denounced <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>'s comments as `` stuff and nonsense.'' The Democrats oppose the Bush-backed plan because it is `` ill timed, ill considered and damaging ... helping only the richest of our citizens and unfair to the middle class,'' he said. The capital gains tax cut is part of a huge budget bill before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The package would be contentious even without the tax fight, because it also contains changes in the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> catastrophic health coverage plan, new federal child care programs, and dozens of other issues with divided support. Nearly buried beneath the controversial issues is the bill's underlying purpose, which is reducing the federal deficit Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, D-Minn., said a review of the bill showed that much of the deficit-reduction in the package was `` disingenuous,'' and after three years the bill would be adding to the red ink Still, <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON> said he would probably vote for the bill if it includes the GOP-supported capital gains tax cut. He did n't put that in the `` disingenuous'' category, but included figures showing that it, too, would begin adding billions of dollars to the deficit after an initial period of added revenues.
