y scheme, which began before the company acquired the subsidiary in 1986. The bribery scheme allegedly began in 1982 when the company was known as <ORGANIZATION> Lee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> and continued two years after its acquisition by <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lamberth </PERSON> was a stockholder of the company and became head of the subsidiary following its acquisition by <PERSON> Whittaker </PERSON>. Court papers said <PERSON> Lamberth </PERSON> hid the scheme from Whittaker officials. The bribes allegedly were funneled to <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> through defense consultants <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Marlowe </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Muldoon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Illeman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Marlowe </PERSON> is cooperating with the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s continuing investigation of Pentagon procurement fraud dubbed `` Operation Ill Wind.'' <PERSON> Muldoon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Illeman </PERSON> have not been charged. <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON>, who pleaded guilty to taking bribes from <PERSON> Marlowe </PERSON> as part of an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> undercover sting, signed authorizations that greatly enhanced the value of two contracts the company obtained to help the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> develop a battlefield air traffic control system, court papers said. <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> signed papers increasing the value of one contract from $ 600,000 to $ 2.5 million, according to the papers, and also authorized the enhancement of another contract's value from $ 540,000 to $ 3.6 million. He also authorized the transfer to <ORGANIZATION> Lee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> of another contract worth $ 1.6 million when the company that first obtained the deal had difficulty developing software, the court papers said. <PERSON> Lamberth </PERSON> faced a possible 20-year sentence and fines up to $ 500,000 for his guilty pleas to conspiracy and bribery. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Tassel </PERSON> could be sentenced to up to 15 years and fined $ 250,000 for his bribery plea. <ORGANIZATION> Hilton </ORGANIZATION> scheduled a Dec. 15 sentencing proceeding for both defendants, who have agreed to cooperate with the investigation.
