<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> says it is in buyout talks and published reports indicate <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has offered about $ 3 billion for the film and television production company. In a statement today, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> said its board met Monday night to review its discussions about a possible sale of the company and adjourned the meeting until Wednesday, when it expects `` further action will be taken.'' In active trading early today on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> was down 25 cents a share at $ 26.12 -LCB-. It had risen $ 5.25 a share on Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> declined comment today on the reports that it had received a buyout offer from <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION>, which previously had indicated an interest in buying a movie studio. A <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> spokesman failed to return a telephone call immediately today, but the company declined coment on Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the Atlanta-based soft drink maker that owns 49 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s stock, said Monday it was aware <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> was in talks and would consider whatever recommendation may be made, but declined further comment. <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> triggered a sharp runup in its stock price Monday when it announced that it was `` in discussions with a third party involving the acquisition for cash of all of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s outstanding shares.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Dow