<SECOND>PM-Finance Meeting, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0030,0812</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Powers Driving Down Dollar's Value</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 6-19, Meanwhile ..., to UPDATE with Camdessus,
Conable speeches delivered. A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese and West German central banks today intervened in currency markets for the second consecutive day, driving down the value of the dollar in an effort to reduce the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. The intervention followed broader action on Monday when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> joined the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> and West German <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> in concerted dollar selling. The actions are in line with a weekend statement by the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> industrial countries _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> _ expressing displeasure with the dollar's strength and fear that its rise in recent months could blunt improvement in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. A strong dollar hurts the trade gap by making <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods more expensive on foreign markets, while lowering the price of imports to American consumers. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar today fell 0.15 yen to a closing 142.80 Japanese yen. It was quoted at the same level later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency was worth 1.9035 West German marks in early trading. On Friday, before the <ORGANIZATION> G-7 </ORGANIZATION> meeting, the dollar bought 146 yen and 1.95 marks. Meanwhile, the world's financial officials began meetings today of the 152-nation <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and its sister lending organization, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Delegates to the meeting are discussing a range of topics from the deterioration of the environment in developing countries, the Third World's crushing $ 1.3 trillion debt burden, and the movement of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and Hungry from communism to free-market economies. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON>, managing director of the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>, pushed today for a doubling of the fund's resources from the current $ 120 billion, but ran into resistance from <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which has veto power over the matter. `` The fund has to be of credible size, so that it gives confidence to the membership and to financial markets that it could respond adequately to any unexpected shock, such as those of the mid 1970s and early 1980s,'' he said. On Third World debt, <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON> called on private banks to step up their lending to developing countries, even as they are forced to write off old debt as part of Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s debt strategy. `` It is now vital to establish the necessary conditions to bring about a more appropriate contribution from the private sector,'' he said. World Bank President <PERSON> Barber </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conable </PERSON> said economic development must be coupled with new efforts to preserve the environment in Third World countries. `` It will be impossible to improve the quality of life ... unless we do much more to conserve our global environment,'' he said, singling out a reduction in carbon monoxide emissions, which contribute to global warming, as a goal. He also said the Third World, which spends $ 200 billion a year on defense, more than its combined expenditure on health and education, must devote fewer resources to the military if it expects to prosper. `` Developing countries on one side, and their arms suppliers and creditors on the other, must adapt to a world where budgets are tight,'' he said. `` ... In evaluating their military expenditures, governments should be realistic, but they also should remember the human consequences of these choices.'' On Monday, officials attending the meetings expressed satisfaction with the results of the intervention. French Finance Minister <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Beregovoy </PERSON> told reporters it reflected `` the reassertion of our common will to cooperate in monetary terms.'' <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> said a decline in the dollar was `` appropriate and reasonable'' and pronounced the action by central banks `` obviously quite successful.'' On other fronts Monday: _ <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> pushed for expansion of his Third World debt strategy, announced in March, which has so far produced tentative agreements between creditor banks and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> `` Important progress is being made within the strengthened debt strategy. We must now push ahead to ensure that the benefits of the strategy reach a broad range of countries,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which met Monday in preparation for today's meeting of the boards of governors of the two world lending organizations. _ <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryrie </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, offered Polish Finance Minister <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Balcerowicz </PERSON> help in setting up a new financial system <PERSON> Ryrie </PERSON> said the efforts are centering on creating a new banking system. He said `` two or three'' Western European banks, which he declined to name, have already expressed an interest.
