 The stock market was higher in moderate trading today, but had given back some earlier gains. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 15.39 points to 2,674.58 at noon EDT. The blue-chip indicator was up 17.29 points an hour earlier. On Monday it fell 22.42 points. Advancing issues outpaced decliners by a margin of nearly 2 to 1 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 814 issues up, 434 down and 527 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 69.13 million shares. The stock market got a slight boost early in the day from a government report that showed surprising strength in new factory orders for durable goods. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that factory orders for `` big ticket'' durable items such as cars, airplanes and machinery, rose 3.8 percent in August, the biggest advance this year. However, the July data was revised downward from down 2.2 percent to down 2.5 percent, more than expected. Orders in June had risen 1.3 percent. Also, a closely-watched section of the report showed that non-defense capital goods had dropped 9.8 percent to $ 37.4 billion. Economists use this category as a barometer of business investment plans. `` What we're seeing is a bargain-hunting phase helped along by program trading,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON>, vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. A sharp rise in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s stock market overnight also gave some support to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, analysts said The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks was up 0.99 to 192.27. On the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <O