<HEAD>For Release Sunday Oct. 1 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nose Jobs: Profile of U.S. Minivans Changing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Minivans-Who's Who</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The face of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s minivans has undergone plastic surgery and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> may not like <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s nose job. Ever since small passenger vans caught the fancy of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> buyers, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has commanded a dominant share of the market. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> is hoping its long-hooded minivans will compel <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> owners to switch makes. While the auto market as a whole likely will shrink during the next year, there are predictions of continued growth in minivans, a segment which has seen rapid expansion since 1983, when <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> introduced the Dodge Caravan and the <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voyager </ORGANIZATION>. The minivan market actually is older than that. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> imported a compact van starting in 1950 and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in the early 1960s sold a <ORGANIZATION> Falcon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wagon </ORGANIZATION>, a half-foot shorter than its current Aerostar minivan. Since the minivan's popularity was ignited seven years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has commanded more than 50 percent of the segment of the light-truck market, which includes minivans. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s share is beginning to slip as the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerostar </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> MPV grow in popularity. The unknown in the minivan formula is how much of the market <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> will get. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> executives have conceded they will lose some of their share, perhaps a percentage point or two. `` But we expected that,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the company's vehicle-making arm. While <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has slapped big incentives on many of its vehicles, the Voyager and Caravan have been exempt. The patients in <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s plastic surgery are the <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> APV </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pontiac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sport </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Oldsmobile </PERSON> <PERSON> Silhouette </PERSON>, rakishly styled minivans made at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tarrytown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, assembly plant. Over the past few months, the company has given plant employees loaner vans to drive around the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> countryside to let folks get an eyeful of the futuristic-looking vehicles. The <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> minivan was originally for the corporation's <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION> and Chevrolet divisions, and <PERSON> Oldsmobile </PERSON> was added later, said a source speaking on condition of anonymity. Capacity of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tarrytown </LOCATION> plant is about 200,000 minivans a year and the mix among the three divisions can be changed relatively easily. Like other minivan makers, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> officials expect buyers to come from those looking at sedans and station wagons and, to a smaller extent, minivan owners ready to trade in their vehicles. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> is banking on some of those current minivan buyers being intrigued by the shape of the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> versions. The plastic-bodied vehicles sport a snout that would have made Cyrano de Bergerac jealous. Analyst <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said he thinks the new <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> minivans are quite attractive. The front-wheel-drive vehicles join the conventionally styled <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Astro </ORGANIZATION>, which is being offered in four-wheel drive for 1990, in the assault on <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s hold on the minivan market. All <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s minivans are front-wheel drive. `` It's the biggest threat that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> minivans have received to date,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. `` There really has n't been anything that would serve as a direct substitute; the others have either been smaller or rear-wheel drive.'' The minivan battle is n't just between <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> continues to offer its Aerostar, and Japanese companies are hoping to grab larger pieces of the minivan pie. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is n't sitting still, either. It is offering a Town & amp; Country version of the minivan, more expensive than the Caravan or Voyager but loaded with extras, including leather seats and a compass. `` We'll sell out two -LRB- minivan -RRB- plants,'' <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON> said, speaking of the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, factories. <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON> estimated the introduction of the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> minivans will add about 200,000 of the vehicles to the road next year, cutting slightly into <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s share. Those new purchasers, he added, will come primarily from potential station-wagon buyers. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is offering no station wagons for 1990. Sales of minivans last year amounted to 725,081 units, a 21.1 percent increase over the year before. The vehicle's share of the light-truck market has climbed to 13.8 percent last year from 7.4 percent in 1985.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 1</NOTE>
