<HEAD>BAT Announces Major Restructuring</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd graf pvs with Goldsmith reaction;
SUBS 7th graf pvs, `The Hoylake... to conform; PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `Hoylake
has...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, which is fending off a hostile $ 22 billion bid from <ORGANIZATION> Hoylake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, on Tuesday announced a major restructuring that includes the sale of its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retail operations. BAT said it would reshape itself to concentrate on tobacco and fast-growing financial services. Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, the Anglo-French financier heading <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION>'s bid, said he welcomed BAT's plan as a `` first step'' to the `` unbundling'' plan he has proposed. He said he would pursue his takeover attempt and said the bidding group for BAT would vote in favor of the restructuring. The British conglomerate said it would sell its retailing interests in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which include <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fifth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Avenue </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION>'s stores, as well as other smaller businesses. It said it would create two new publicly held companies by giving its existing shareholders shares in its British retailing company <ORGANIZATION> Argos </ORGANIZATION>, as well as shares in a combination of its paper companies <ORGANIZATION> Wiggins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teape </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>. BAT also plans to buy back 10 percent of its shares and to `` significantly increase'' its dividend for 1989. These measures require shareholder approval, and BAT has called a special shareholders meeting for Oct. 19. The <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> bidding group has offered $ 14.14 worth of securities for each BAT share. <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> has suspended the offer while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> state insurance commissions review its proposed change of ownership of <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> has vowed to `` unbundle'' BAT by selling off all its non-tobacco interests <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> and other critics of BAT have complained that BAT's share price does n't reflect the true value of its underlying businesses and is constrained by the relatively slow growth of its tobacco businesses Now BAT is seeking to fight off the <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> bid by addressing this problem. The <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> offer, however, has attracted little interest from BAT's shareholders and analysts have said that the bidders will have to increase their offer and include some cash in order to succeed. `` We can now accelerate the strategy of concentrating on financial services and tobacco,'' BAT Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said in a statement. `` The board now believes that the five decisive steps will continue the long-term development of the group and address our concern about the value of BAT shares on the stock market compared to the underlying value of the businesses.'' BAT said it envisions that tobacco will provide steady earnings growth and strong cash flow which will complement the more rapid growth expected in financial services during the 1990s. These two businesses will represent `` an exceptionally powerful combination'' to enhance shareholder value in the years ahead, it said. BAT said tobacco and financial services now contribute about $ 1.5 billion and $ 13.36 billion, respectively, to its earnings. BAT forecast pre-tax profit of $ 3.2 billion this year, a 22 percent increase over 1988. Earnings per share also were forecast to rise by 22 percent to $ 1.23.
</TEXT>
