<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Meet, Break Up Until Early Evening</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, The ministers ..., with two grafs to UPDATE
with meeting postponed. SUBS 13th graf, Late Monday ..., to conform. Subroto
one word is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers scrambled on Tuesday to patch together an agreement on their production plans for the rest of the year. The ministers of the 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> gathered in late morning but postponed an early evening meeting to give them more time to come up with a new accord. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> announced the delay, saying `` new thinking -LRB- was -RRB- being developed.'' Shortly before then, an Iranian delegate said his country had offered a new plan for raising the production ceiling in the final quarter of the year. The ministers were arguing over whether they can boost production from their current limit of 19.5 million barrels a day in the final quarter, without upsetting prices. `` It seems -LRB- there will be -RRB- a little increase,'' said a senior member of one delegation, who demanded anonymity. `` But we still have different positions,'' he said. `` It's a slow process.'' `` We have to argue a little,'' said <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalifa </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sabah </PERSON> after the two-hour meeting. `` Otherwise, it would n't be <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>.'' The ministers seemed determined to try to rescue the talks, which were on the verge of collapse Monday evening. `` We have come back from the edge of the precipice,'' said a senior delegate midway through the two-hour long morning meeting. He also demanded anonymity. The ministers were reported close to a deal Monday on raising the production ceiling, but then hit some snags forcing them to postpone formal discussions. Their negotiations _ most taking place in their rooms at a luxury <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> hotel _ have centered on a lifting the ceiling between 20 million barrels a day and 21 million barrels, according to delegates. They also must decide how to distribute any increase among the 13 member nations. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> want bigger shares than now allotted them. Others argue the extra amount should be shared proportionately. Late Monday evening, <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> said, `` We think that -LRB- Tuesday -RRB- could be our last look at the routes to take.'' <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> has predicted demand for the cartel's oil would reach 22 million barrels a day in the October-December period. The cartel's executive body, according to sources, has said prices could reach $ 18 even if the cap were lifted to as much as 21.5 million barrels a day _ but only if all adhered to their quotas. The talks, which began Saturday, are officially held by a monitoring panel made up of <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. The other members _ <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> _ were invited to attend.
