<FIRST>r f AM-AnimalTesting     09-26 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Animal Testing,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cosmetics Industry Says Animal Testing Still Necessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cosmetics industry must have the option of testing its products on animals while trying to develop alternative methods to ensure those products are safe for consumers, an industry spokesman said Tuesday. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavanaugh </PERSON>, president of the Cosmetic, Toiletry and <ORGANIZATION> Fragrance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the industry regards `` the safety of -LRB- its -RRB- consumers as their primary responsibility and highest priority.'' Responding to efforts to ban the use of animals in such product testing, <PERSON> Kavanaugh </PERSON> said the industry is trying to develop alternatives. However, `` makers of personal care products must continue to have the option of using animal research data,'' he said. Animal rights activists who gathered outside the industry news conference argued that alternatives already have been found and are being used. `` Major corporations ... have switched to in vitro or non-animal methods, including cell-culture techniques, testing on membranes, computer modeling,'' <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> of People for the <ORGANIZATION> Ethical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treatment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animals </ORGANIZATION> told reporters. The nation's largest cosmetics company, <LOCATION> Avon </LOCATION>, has invested millions of dollars to develop such non-animal testing alternatives, company spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. However, <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Avons </PERSON> backs the industry association position on testing because `` there is no one test or even a series of tests that could be developed for everybody's products.'' `` Until everybody has developed alternatives, we feel they ought to have the option of testing,'' he said. Eight states _ <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> _ are considering legislation to ban animal testing for cosmetics, household and pharmaceutical products.
</TEXT>
