<FIRST>u f AM-Poland-MBAs Bjt   09-26 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-MBAs, Bjt,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lessons In Capitalism for New Breed Of East Bloc Managers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With much of the communist world planning economic retooling, lessons in capitalism await at the first business administration schools designed to turn a new breed of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc managers into competitive, market-oriented executives. A fundamentally different business environment is developing as economically weak <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and increasingly troubled <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> cut restraints on domestic entrepreneurs, demand that state-run enterprises be profitable and open their borders to foreign investors. A handful of executive training programs are being organized to meld Western management techniques with the realities of Eastern European business. `` Intellectually, these are not new concepts,'' says <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Kosminski </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor creating the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> to open Oct. 23 near the capital. `` But let's say that in our system of management, there was no use up to now for that kind of approach ... because of a system that was obviously in basic contradiction to sound business practices.'' <PERSON> Kosminski </PERSON>'s school will offer the first <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc equivalent of a Master's of Business Administration. In addition, Western companies are opening business skills schools in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. During more than four decades of centralized planning for captive consumers in communist-ruled nations, business decisions were made by remote bureaucratic ministries. There was litle need to worry about developing hot-selling products, finding market niches, advertising and packaging. Motivating workers, pleasing customers, direct foreign trade and cost saving largely are new concepts for the would-be East bloc entrepreneur. `` Our business people are used to thinking in socialist conditions: ` I produce because I must cover the social need.' This is nonsense,'' said <PERSON> Bogda </PERSON> <PERSON> Zukowska </PERSON>, a journalist for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s Economic Life newspaper `` Now they are starting to think, ` I must produce because I would like to sell and earn money, and I must do my best to cope with the market, what the market needs and the cost of production,''' she said. Hopes for resurrecting <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s economy hinge largely on foreign investment and domestic private enterprise. But Poles must learn how the West does business when there is competition for customers who have a range of choices, and foreign investors must learn how business works in what <PERSON> Kosminski </PERSON> calls <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s `` negotiable'' economy. At the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, 48 Polish business people, some private entrepreneurs and others sent by their state-owned enterprises, have signed up for the first semester at a cost of about $ 250. The school also will offer orientation programs for Western managers interested in doing business in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc and offer consulting services from students who are doing case studies. In <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> was established in November 1988 through a joint venture with Italian organizations. A 10-month `` junior executive'' program is offered along with lecture series for managers. A Canadian-Polish partnership is starting the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> this fall, offering programs for executives and courses on `` English for business'' and `` How to start your own business.'' Polish regulations on starting private businesses were loosened this year under a privatization of enterprises considered crucial for turning the economy toward capitalism, filling empty stores and reviving commercial links with the West. Before these new businesses _ and those being salvaged from the socialist sector _ can enter the competitive market abroad or prosper at home, the entrepreneurs will need new techniques, <PERSON> Kosminski </PERSON> said. The classes at his school are `` designed to train the elite of Polish managers as efficient, market oriented and globally oriented, socially responsible, competent and reliable business partners,'' according to a prospectus. Polish professors and visiting lecturers will offer courses in Polish and English _ materials on such subjects as international marketing and finance are virtually unavailable in Polish _ to be held one week a month through four semesters over two years so participants can continue to work. Students will learn accounting, business law and quality control, as well as business protocol, how to organize receptions and what to say in press releases. `` They will combine a knowledge of international business and international standards of doing business with local specificity,'' <PERSON> Kosminski </PERSON> said. Polish managers also will be needed to help Western executives investing in the country maneuver through logistical and bureaucratic obstacles. `` Our business environment is still exotic,'' <PERSON> Kosminski </PERSON> said, with multiple currency markets, supplies from typing paper to office chairs virtually unavailable and an endless string of `` arrangements'' needed to handle the `` negotiable'' bureaucracy. `` It is difficult for foreign businesses,'' he said. `` That's why they need intermediaries, people who know both cultures, and I think some of our graduates might be able to play that role.
</TEXT>
