<HEAD>IBM Reveals Big Plans for Its Personal Computer Design</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Tuesday revealed ambitious plans for <ORGANIZATION> Micro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Architecture </ORGANIZATION>, its patent-covered design for the way information moves around inside its personal computers <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> also said that Micro Channel is theoretically capable of transferring data at 160 million bytes per second, eight times as fast as its current speed limit. A byte represents one letter or number. The announcements were intended in part to counter the momentum of a standard that is being pushed by the `` Gang of Nine'' _ rival makers of personal computers such as <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> recently said it will begin shipping the first computer built to that rival standard in October <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said it intends to use Micro Channel not only with personal computers, but eventually with high-speed workstations and even mainframe computers _ a landmark in the growing importance of personal computers. Although <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s mainframe line uses a different system for internal data transfer, the company said <ORGANIZATION> Micro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Channel </ORGANIZATION> would eventually become the way that mainframes communicate with personal computers and workstations. As a sign of the Micro Channel's importance, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said the design would form the heart of a new line of workstations that will replace the relatively unsuccessful RT PC late this year or early in 1990. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> has tried to make Micro Channel into an industry standard, but companies that have come out with compatible machines under license to <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> have had limited success. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is hoping that Tuesday's announcements will convince customers that Micro Channel, announced in 1987, is the wave of the future. `` They're trying to show a sense of order in a potentially chaotic environment,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> executive who is now a consultant in <LOCATION> Scarsdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s rivals say their personal computer standard is better because there are more add-on devices that will work with it. But <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> said there are more than 1,000 add-on devices made by other companies to enhance the <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> Personal System-2, and more in the works. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chips </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> both said Tuesday they were working with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> on developing sets of chips that other companies could use to make compatible add-on devices for the Micro Channel. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> reaffirmed that it would come out with a personal computer built on <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s latest microprocessor, the high-speed i486, by the end of the year. It cut prices and introduced new variations on several existing models in its Personal System-2 line.
