<HEAD>BAT Reshapes Itself In Attempt to Defeat Hoylake Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday proposed the sale of its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailing businesses as part of a restructuring the conglomerate hoped would defeat <ORGANIZATION> Hoylake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 22 billion hostile takeover bid. The planned restructuring was intended to enhance the value of <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION>'s stock, company chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said in a statement. Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Anglo-French </LOCATION> financier who leads <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION>, said he welcomed BAT's proposal as a first step toward his plans for breaking up the conglomerate. <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> said he would not give up his takeover attempt, which has been suspended while the group tries to overcome regulatory obstacles. Securities analysts said BAT's proposals would enhance the value of the British conglomerate's stock and was likely to be approved by its shareholders. But they said <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> could still bid for what is left of BAT. <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> has offered 13.4 billion pounds, or $ 22 billion, in securities for BAT. BAT said it would reshape itself to concentrate on its tobacco business, which is steady and generates cash, and its fast-growing financial services segment. This would be a significant departure from its previous strategy of gradually diversifying away from tobacco. The retained businesses are expected to account for 80 percent of <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION>'s forecast 1989 pre-tax profit of $ 3.2 billion, BAT said. The British conglomerate said it would sell its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailing business, which includes 46 <ORGANIZATION> Saks </ORGANIZATION> Fifth Avenue stores and 24 <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Field </ORGANIZATION>'s stores. The two retailers have combined annual sales of $ 2 billion. These and other planned, smaller divestitures could fetch a total of $ 2.4 billion, analysts said. BAT said it also would create two new publicly held companies by giving its existing shareholders a stake in its British retailing company <ORGANIZATION> Argos </ORGANIZATION>, as well as stock in a combination of its paper companies, <PERSON> Wiggins </PERSON> <PERSON> Teape </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION> is based in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. BAT said it also would buy back 10 percent of its shares _ which would cost 1.24 billion pounds, or $ 2 billion, at Tuesday's closing price on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The company also pledged to significantly increase its dividends. The total dividend for 1989 could go as high as 30 pence, or 48 cents, per share, a 49 percent increase over the previous year's payment, BAT said. BAT called a special shareholders meeting for Oct. 19 to vote on the proposed restructuring. BAT stock rose 2 pence, or 3 cents, a share to close at 818 pence, or $ 13.17. <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> has suspended its $ 14.14 a share offer while state insurance commissioners in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> review its proposed change of ownership of <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> has vowed to break up BAT by selling off all its non-tobacco interests The group and other critics of BAT have complained the conglomerate's stock price does not reflect the true value of its underlying businesses because it is constrained by the relatively slow growth of its tobacco business. <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON>, in an interview on British radio, said the plan would give existing shareholders the benefit of splitting up BAT, rather than allowing <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> to take a profit from dismantling the conglomerate. <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> would vote in favor of <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION>'s plan although the investor group was not abandoning its bid. `` The point is that they've made a first step'' in the direction of realizing a higher share value for BAT shareholders, which is the basis of the <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> argument, <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. The <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> offer has attracted little interest from BAT's shareholders and analysts have said that the bidding group would have to increase its bid and include some cash to succeed <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, an analyst with the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` It does seem likely that they -LRB- shareholders -RRB- would approve these -LRB- BAT -RRB- proposals because it gives them a bird in the hand.'' It could take <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> nine months to get regulatory clearance in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said. `` It's a useful start,'' said <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Utley </PERSON>, an analyst with <PERSON> Laing </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cruickshank </PERSON>. `` It will enhance shareholder value, but not necessarily enough to defeat a serious bid.''
