<HEAD>Executive Gets 18 Months in Mail Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Wall Street executive who pleaded guilty to three counts of mail fraud for for allegedly bribing a former governor of <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION> has been sentenced to 18 months in prison. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> on Monday also placed <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Abba </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> on five years' probation, fined him $ 100,000 and ordered him to repay the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> $ 300,000. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bond underwriting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, pleaded guilty July 14 to three counts of mail fraud. He had been accused of funneling $ 70,000 to former Guam Gov. <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bordallo </PERSON>'s unsuccessful 1986 re-election campaign. In exchange, <PERSON> Bordallo </PERSON> allegedly agreed to generate support for a $ 300 million housing bond issue underwritten by <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bordallo </PERSON> was acquitted in February 1986 of accepting bribes from <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> but was convicted on 10 counts of government corruption. He served as governor from 1975-79 and from 1983-87. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> had faced a maximum 15 years' imprisonment and a $ 750,000 fine in addition to restitution payments, according to <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney from <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION>. The three counts referred to money bilked from the Guam Program Development Fund and a `` lulling letter'' assuring fund authorities that the transactions were legal. A December 1987 indictment charged <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> with preparing phony invoices that were sent to the bank entrusted with the fund money. The bank paid the money to <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, who spent $ 25,000 to buy campaign paraphernalia _ including parasols, shirts and hats _ for <PERSON> Bordallo </PERSON>'s unsuccessful re-election bid, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> has said. Authorities said <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> made his contributions after <PERSON> Bordallo </PERSON> was promised that he would receive campaign contributions if he supported the bond issue to build homes. The bond was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Guam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in 1985. <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> has denied any wrongdoing. In exchange for <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s guilty pleas, 46 other counts alleging bribery, conspiracy, and wire and mail fraud were dismissed. The case was moved from <LOCATION> Guam </LOCATION>, 3,800 miles west of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, because of extensive pretrial publicity on the island. Twelve of the original counts against <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> were related directly to Guam. The balance referred to fraud involving the use of the <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Americas </ORGANIZATION> in transactions that did not involve the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory. In August 1987, Gov. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ada </PERSON> sued <ORGANIZATION> Matthews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> for the return of $ 14 million in fees the firm had received, as well as $ 250 million in punitive damages. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said in July the suit had been settled, but he released no details.
