<SECOND>AM-Auto Production Cuts, Bjt,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Production Cuts, Dipping Sales May Mean Rocky Labor Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Auto production and sales are dropping, and that could mean layoffs around the time the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union begins gearing up for 1990 contract talks with the Big Three automakers, analysts said Tuesday. The 1990 model year technically begins Oct. 1, although some new models have been on sale for months. Nevertheless, some of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s buyer incentives on its new cars and trucks took effect before the vehicles officially went on sale. That suggests the industry is grappling with a host of potential problems in moving its product. Much of the recent focus has been on <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>. `` Some of us believe that <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> will close some plants permanently in the next few months,'' said analyst <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He said the disparity between <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s production capacity and its market share would indicate four plants could be closed Last week, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> announced it was idling its <LOCATION> Lakewood </LOCATION> plant in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> in March, joining recently closed plants in <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>.; <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mo </PERSON>.; and <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> has scheduled some temporary production cuts next month at a half-dozen car and truck plants, lasting a week or two apiece, because of swollen vehicle inventories <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has said it temporarily would halt production at a car and truck plant in early October. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has n't announced any temporary plant closings for October Analyst <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> estimated that fourth quarter production this year would be 10 percent to 15 percent below last year's levels. Production cuts may be hastened by auto dealers, who have said they wo n't be ordering as many 1990 vehicles as they did during the 1989 model year. There have been estimates that dealer orders may fall by as much as 30 percent below last year's levels. Analysts also said recent sales activity, including a 12.7 percent jump in mid-September car and truck purchases reported Monday, supports a theory that current sales are being `` borrowed'' from the fourth quarter, as consumers rush to beat 1990 model year price increases. `` I suspect sales are going to be rather soft in the fourth quarter,'' <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> said. Softer sales point to lower production, increased layoffs and a higher potential for labor problems in the last three months of the year, as the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> prepares for Big Three contract talks. One <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Tuesday that union officials were n't alarmed but were monitoring production levels and possible layoffs. <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> contracts with each of the Big Three automakers expire Sept. 14, 1990. Preparations for the negotiations, which open next summer, begin in earnest during the first three months of next year. By then, the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> will be looking back on any temporary layoffs and ahead to the closing of the <LOCATION> Lakewood </LOCATION> plant, which will idle about 2,200 workers. `` I think labor relations are going to be very murky in the next few months,'' <PERSON> Kirnan </PERSON> said. In addition to potential layoffs, one question is the kind of style <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Yokich </PERSON>, the new head of the union's <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, will bring to the bargaining table. This June, <PERSON> Yokich </PERSON> succeeded <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ephlin </PERSON>, who retired. Under <PERSON> Ephlin </PERSON>'s leadership, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and the union developed cooperative programs that injected worker participation in some management decisions, but also created the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s largest internal political fight in the past 40 years. Dissidents under the `` New Directions'' banner have criticized <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> leadership for eroding workers' rights through joint programs. But New Directions leader <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said he liked <PERSON> Yokich </PERSON>'s sharp criticism of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s planned <LOCATION> Lakewood </LOCATION> closing <PERSON> Yokich </PERSON> said the move undermines efforts to develop a new relationship between the company and the union.
