with quotes, details, minor editing; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Citizens and <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sovran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 4.7 billion merger Tuesday that will create the nation's 14th-largest bank. C & amp; S, based in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Sovran </LOCATION>, based in <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, will have total assets of $ 47 billion and almost 1,000 offices in seven states from <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. Under a newly formed holding company called <ORGANIZATION> Avantor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the two banks will maintain dual headquarters and retain current management. The merger comes five months after C & amp; S fought off a takeover bid by <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Unlike that proposal, the <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S-Sovran deal is a friendly merger. In a joint statement, <ORGANIZATION> Sovran </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gornto </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and C & amp; S Chairman <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> A. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said the deal combines the advantages of size and market strength with success in community-based banking. `` We are creating a large, nationally competitive franchise with a powerful presence in major high-growth markets, and we're underwriting it with superior credit quality,'' they said in a statement `` This is a company that will be completely focused on service, efficiency and profitability,'' the statement said. The boards of the two companies have approved the agreement. Final approval from shareholders and federal and state regulators is expected in the first quarter of 1990. Both companies will remain in existence as subsidiaries of the new umbrella organization. A new board of directors will be established with 15 members from Sovran and 14 from C & amp; S. `` It's a big deal,'' said <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> <PERSON> Shockley </PERSON>, a banking industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It's going to create the powerhouse in the Southeast. C & amp; S has 489 bank offices in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Sovran has 487 offices in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Scredon </PERSON>, a C & amp; S spokesman in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said the merger has been discussed on and off for about two years. `` We feel it's a perfect fit,'' <PERSON> Scredon </PERSON> said. `` We do n't overlap ... and we each double our market presence. We both feel it could n't be any better.'' <PERSON> Scredon </PERSON> said customers should not see any immediate changes when the merger is completed, but once the two institutions pool resources new services probably will be offered. Under the merger agreement, each of Sovran's 59.8 million shares of outstanding common stock will convert into 1.23 shares of the new company's common stock. Each of C & amp; S's 62 million shares of outstanding common stock will convert into 1.0 shares of the new company's common stock. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> will become chairman and chief executive officer of the new company while retaining his position at <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gornto </PERSON> will become chairman of the new company's executive committee and will retain his position at the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> bank. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bottorff </PERSON>, Sovran's president and chief operating officer, will be president and chief operating officer of <ORGANIZATION> Avantor </ORGANIZATION> and would become chief executive of the new company upon <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s retirement At that time, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, now president of <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; S, would become <ORGANIZATION> Avantor </ORGANIZATION> chairman. Last spring, <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, N.C.-based <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> targeted C & amp; S in a $ 2.4 billion takeover bid. C & amp; S officials refused to discuss the proposal, and <ORGANIZATION> NCNB </ORGANIZATION> eventually withdrew the offer.
