<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Independent television stations Tuesday took a swing at baseball owners for increasingly limiting television viewing of the `` American Pastime'' to homes with cable TV. Recent agreements giving cable companies rights to <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> games and a four-year, $ 400 million contract that gives the <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> cable network rights to Wednesday and Sunday night baseball games typify the flight of sports to cable TV, said <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> Padden </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Assocation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Padden </PERSON>, in a letter Tuesday to <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON>, the new commisioner of <ORGANIZATION> Major </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baseball </ORGANIZATION>, said that given `` the clear trends in the cable industry ... it seems likely that legislation will be necessary to preserve sports on free TV.'' But before that happens, `` we ask you to consider mutually voluntary changes'' in the <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> contract, <PERSON> Padden </PERSON> said. `` Specifically, we are concerned about those provisions that restrict our right to broadcast baseball games on Wednesday and Sunday evenings.'' <PERSON> Padden </PERSON> disputed Major League Baseball's assertion that the <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> contract would expand TV viewers' choices. `` Fans will experience a diminution in the supply of baseball,'' <PERSON> Padden </PERSON> said. `` More to the point, you will be restricting access to Major League Baseball only to those who have access to cable, and-or can afford cable rates which average over $ 25 a month. For the ` American Pastime,' we find this contrary to the public interest.'' Calls to the Major League Baseball office in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for comment were not immediately returned. <PERSON> Padden </PERSON>'s letter grew out of a meeting this month in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of TV station executives from 24 of the 26 cities that have Major League Baseball. The executives agreed to try to get <ORGANIZATION> MLB </ORGANIZATION> to alter the <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> contract. The TV executives also were concerned about cable TV contracts for sports at Big 10, <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> 10 and Southeastern Conference schools. They said such contracts point to a day when all sports will be on pay TV. The station executives have enlisted the aid of Sens. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., to press their case in The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has said that local broadcasters are showing 40 percent more professional baseball games now when compared with 1975 and that cable is not siphoning away free TV sports.
