<SECOND>AM-Coors Family, Bjt,0789</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adolph Coors' Great Grandsons Break With Tradition By Borrowing Money</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Adolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>' great grandsons broke with a family tradition of never borrowing money to brew beer when they decided to buy most of <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 425 million. But tradition is as strong as ever at <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> men sit down to lunch every day in the dining room of the mansion <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> built more than a century ago on the brewery grounds. As a 26-year-old immigrant who left <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to avoid military service, <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> founded a modest brewery on the banks of <LOCATION> Clear </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> in 1873, just 14 years after gold-seekers descended on the area. But Coors lacked the gold-seekers' gambling instincts; his cardinal rules were to brew good beer and stay out of debt doing it. Over the years, the founder passed on his cautious, self-reliant streak to his son, <PERSON> Adolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and then to the grandsons, <PERSON> William </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>. The family business grew into the nation's fourth-largest brewery The announcement Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> was going to pay $ 425 million for Detroit-based <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION>'s brewing assets represented a break with the past. The deal will give <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> 18 <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> brands, five <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> breweries and two can plants. If completed as expected early next year, the acquisition will boost <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>' annual sales to nearly $ 3 billion. Coors would become the nation's No. 3 brewer, behind <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. To complete the deal, <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> will have to borrow an estimated $ 300 million. And because the Coors family has assiduously avoided such borrowing throughout its history _ <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> traditionally has paid cash when it wanted something _ the company has no bond rating. Still, it is not expected to have trouble finding or repaying the money. `` The company believes in a strong balance sheet. If you have a strong balance sheet, it enables you to make a move like we have with <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Klugman </PERSON>, vice president of development for <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. The Coors family controls 100 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>' Class A voting stock and about a third of its nonvoting, publicly traded Class B stock. The Stroh acquisition is a clear indication that the fourth-generation <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> brothers _ <PERSON> Peter </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> _ are firmly in control one year after the torch was passed by their uncle, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, and their father, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, in a reorganization. All five of <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>' sons attend to family business. While <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, 43, runs the beer-brewing operation and was the key figure in the Stroh deal, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, 44, is president of <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 46, the oldest son, is head of <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Porcelain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos </ORGANIZATION>. The two other brothers, <PERSON> Grover </PERSON>, 39, and <PERSON> John </PERSON>, 33, have lesser roles in the family business _ <PERSON> Grover </PERSON> heads <ORGANIZATION> MicroLithics </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary that produces military systems, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> is in charge of <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>' customer satisfaction division. `` <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> and I are running the business,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, when asked what role his uncle, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, 73, the company chairman, and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, 72, vice chairman, continue to play in the firm's day-to-day operations. Despite the decision to incur major debt, the Coors family remains a strong believer in tradition. Every day that business does not take them out of town, the brothers lunch inside the 22-room Coors mansion, the official family residence on the brewery grounds that <PERSON> Adolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON> built. That kind of traditionalism over the years has been reflected in the Coors' politically conservative image, especially concerning organized labor. A year after Brewery Workers union went on strike in 1977 over <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>' desire to subject its workers to lie-detector tests, Coors replaced the strikers with non-union employees. That earned the company the enmity of national labor and triggered a national consumer boycott by the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> that lasted 10 years. The boycott ended after <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> pledged not to interfere with union organizing efforts at <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>, although brewery workers rejected the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union in an election in December 1988. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, a prominent conservative and friend of former President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, was an outspoken member of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s so-called `` kitchen cabinet'' during <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s early presidential years An active supporter of anti-communist causes, <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> also testified on behalf of Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Iran-Contra hearings. Documents released during those hearings showed that a $ 65,000 donation by <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> wound up in a <LOCATION> Swiss </LOCATION> bank account used to buy arms for Nicaraguan rebels.
