<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> ministers stepped up bargaining Tuesday in a last-ditch effort to increase the oil cartel's production ceiling above 19.5 million barrels a day for the rest of 1989 without sending prices into a freefall. The 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries three times postponed what was expected to be a final round of talks to consider a new Iranian proposal. Talks were to resume Wednesday evening. `` It has to cook some,'' Iraqi Oil Minister <PERSON> Issam </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Chalabi </PERSON> said of the Iranian plan. But <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> immediately threw cold water on the idea. `` We will not accept it,'' insisted a senior Libyan delegate, who demanded anonymity. Earlier, Iranian Oil Minister <PERSON> Gholamreza </PERSON> <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> said his country had offered a plan to raise the production ceiling in the last quarter of the year. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> suggested hiking the cap to between 20.5 million barrels a day and 21 million barrels. The ministers talks have centered on raising the production cap from the current 19.5 million barrel limit to a level between 20 million barrels a day and 21 million barrels, according to delegates. The additional amount under the Iranian plan would be divided under a formula that would meet the demands of <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> for bigger shares of the production pie. All countries would get larger individual quotas, meaning they could pump more in the last quarter than now but some would see their percentage share of the total output shrink. `` It seems -LRB- there will be -RRB- a little increase,'' said a senior member of one delegation, who demanded anonymity. `` But we still have different positions. It's a slow process.'' `` There are some members that are still taking a very hard line,'' said another delegate, also on condition of anonymity. The meeting began Saturday with the delegates arguing over whether the market was strong enough to absorb an increase in production without sending prices tumbling. The cartel has been overproducing, pumping more crude than allowed under an output agreement signed in June. Analysts' estimate <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production at about 22 million barrels daily Gasoline prices at the pump were likely to remain about the same or even fall a few cents in the long term if production were increased, according to analysts. The average price of a basket of crudes monitored by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> was recently about $ 1 under the cartel's benchmark of $ 18 a 42-gallon barrel. West Texas Intermediate, the major <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> grade, has been trading at about $ 19.50 to $ 20 a barrel. The ministers were reported close to an agreement Monday but ran into trouble getting all countries to sign on to the deal. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> have been producing well beyond their individual quotas in an effort to press their case for higher shares. Others countries, though, are unwilling to give in to those two nations and want any increase shared proportionately. Analysts say <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> have been producing as much as double their quotas of about 1 million barrels each. The ministers could extend the current ceiling until the end of the year. But analysts say that might leave the impression of disarray in the cartel's ranks. It also could prompt some countries to widen their taps to take advantage of the firm market. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> has predicted that demand in the final quarter will be 22 million barrels a day. The ministers are to meet again in late November to hammer out a production pact for the first six months of 1990. This week's talks were officially held by a monitoring panel made up of <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. The other <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members _ <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> _ were invited to attend.
