<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar retreated further against the Japanese yen during morning trading Wednesday, pressured by central bank dollar-selling, dealers said. Share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> were firmer as they reached a new high. The dollar was changing hands at 141.35 yen at late morning, down 1.45 yen from Tuesday's close of 142.80 yen. After opening at 141.60 yen, the currency ranged from 141.00 to 141.62 yen. Currency dealers said the coordinated intervention, conducted by central banks from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, followed on the heels of a wave of central bank action in overseas market Tuesday, meant to check the dollar's upward trend. The amount of intervention was not immediately known, but it followed similar concerted action by the three central banks Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's central bank, does not comment on its monetary activities. `` The concerted intervention represented a firm commitment by the monetary authorities to contain the dollar's upward move,'' following the weekend meeting of the Group of Seven nations, said a dealer with a major commercial bank in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, who spoke anonymously. At the end of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> meeting, finance ministers and central bankers from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> said in a statement that the dollar's strength was inconsistent with economic fundamentals. On the stock market, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues gained 93.63 points, or 0.26 percent, closing the morning session at 35,538.45, a new high. The Nikkei index posted a 484.11-point gain the previous day for a record closing 35,444.82. Securities dealers said the market mood remained positive after Tuesday's advances, but institutional investors were still cautiously watching the direction of the foreign exchange rates. `` The market was further encouraged by the yen's appreciation against the dollar,'' said a dealer of a major Japanese securities brokerage who spoke anonymously.
