<HEAD>Report: Venezuela Offers New Debt-Reduction Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> has dropped its demands for a 50 percent reduction in its debt to commercial banks and plans to offer new proposals in an attempt to revive negotiations with the financial institutions, according to a published report. The changes were detailed Monday by <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> <PERSON> Fandeo </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s minister of planning, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Tuesday editions. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> said an agreement was near on a $ 600 million interim loan from the banks. The loan would enable the South American nation to meet some interest payments missed over the last several months `` in order to create the atmosphere so the negotiating process could speed up.'' <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, interviewed in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> at the annual meetings of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, said the changes were made to `` accommodate the realities of the banks.'' He was referring to the different legal and accounting rules in differing countries. He added that <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> had not changed its position in response to moves in the last few weeks by three major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks to increase their reserves for bad Third World loans. The moves by the banks were seen as making it more difficult for Third World debtors to restructure their debts. Instead of its 50 percent reduction in its $ 21 billion in loans from commercial banks, a goal the banks rejected, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> will now offer the banks a broad range of options on debt reduction, <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> said. The options would include reducing the debt by various levels, starting at 60 percent and going to below the 35 percent level negotiated in a debt agreement with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Banks also would have the option of making new loans, he said. Offering various debt reduction levels to different banks would make it easier to negotiate than trying to reach agreement on one number among all banks, he said.
