<HEAD>Seaman Furniture Announces Tentative Refinancing Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Seaman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says it had agreed in principle with its banks on a partial repayment plan that would include a fresh $ 42 million investment by <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION>'s investors and members of the <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON> family. <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON> went private two years ago in a $ 360 million buyout arranged by <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION> but ran into trouble making debt payments because of a downturn in its major market, <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. The troubles of the 31-store furniture chain came as an embarrassment to <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION> by raising questions about how thoroughly it had investigated <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON>'s prospects before backing the buyout. The proposal announced Monday would keep <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON> afloat by slashing and stretching out its debt to banks and giving paper instead of cash in payments to junk bond holders until 1996. Creditors would also get an unspecified amount of <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON>'s stock. The deal requires approval by the holders of 90 percent of its junk bonds. The banks have already agreed to it in principle, <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON> said. News of the accord boosted the price of <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON>'s junk bonds, which had lost more than 90 percent of their face value. Its junk bond issue was trading Monday at $ 110 bid and $ 140 asked per $ 1,000 face value, up from about $ 70 bid before the announcement, according to <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, head of junk bond trading at <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` The company's in wonderful shape now, especially with the insertion of the cash,'' <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON>, the chief executive, said in an interview. <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON> said the company has opened five stores in the last 12 months while closing one. A news release said the refinancing will let it `` continue to aggressively explore new sites in 1990 and take advantage of the opportunities we see developing.'' In exchange for $ 265 million in existing bank debt, banks would receive $ 150 million in senior debt, $ 25 million in subordinated pay-in-kind notes and a `` substantial amount of equity,'' <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON> said. The pay-in-kind notes would pay interest in the form of more notes rather than cash until 1996. They would pay interest in cash from then until they mature in 1999. Banks agreed to receive payments of interest but not principal on $ 125 million of their debt from now through Nov. 15, 1992. There would be no payments even of interest on the remaining $ 25 million until that date. The investors who put in the extra $ 42 million would receive senior subordinated notes. The share that each of the investors would put in was not specified. Owners of <PERSON> Seaman </PERSON>'s roughly $ 83 million in outstanding junk bonds would get $ 20.8 million face value of new pay-in-kind notes and 8 percent of the stock in <LOCATION> Seaman </LOCATION> in exchange for 90 percent of those junk bonds. The terms of those pay-in-kind notes were not specified.
