<HEAD>Record $187.1 Billion in Bonds Issued in First Three Quarters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A record $ 187.1 billion in debt securities was issued to the public in the first three quarters of this year as interest rates dropped, according to a survey. <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, in a preliminary survey released Monday for the first nine months, noted that, on the other hand, the volume of common stock brought to market fell sharply. The survey covers Jan. 1 through Sept. 20. The volume of Treasury bonds and other debt securities issued jumped to $ 187.1 billion during the first three quarters, up from $ 181.4 billion in the same period last year and surpassing the previous nine-month record of $ 184.2 billion in the first three quarters of 1987. The sales were stimulated by falling interest rates, <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> noted. When interest rates decline, bond prices rise. The rate on the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s key 30-year bond, for example, has fallen from 9.08 percent on Jan. 3, the first trading day of the year, to 8.23 percent in early trading Monday. The yield on the closely watched bond dropped on Aug. 2 to 7.84 percent, its lowest level since April 1987. While the total volume of bonds issued expanded, `` junk'' bonds fared poorly during the period, the consulting firm said. It blamed the recent shakeout in the junk bond market for the smallest number of the high-risk, high-yield bonds being issued since 1984. Ninety-five junk bond offerings were made during the first nine months, down from 115 in the same period last year. The total volume of junk bonds offered was nearly stable, at $ 19.28 billion compared with $ 19.36 billion in 1988. But around $ 4 billion of this year's volume was accounted for by the $ 24.53 billion leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, noted <PERSON> Francine </PERSON> <PERSON