ercent and <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON>'s 11 percent <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> is a unit of <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc The 139-year-old <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> has been looking for potential partners since February and announced Aug. 31 it was laying off 300 of its 1,500 white-collar employees nationwide. Chairman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> said the cuts were being made because the family-owned company had been unable to find a partner. <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> also cut back support of civic and industry affairs and advertising, including auto racing sponsorships. Coors' would acquire <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> plants in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Longview </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Allentown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. Can plants to be acquired are in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Longview </LOCATION> <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> also has breweries in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Nuys </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, that will not be acquired, <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Stroh </PERSON> plants are represented by the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>, while <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> workers rejected representation by the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> last December. `` We've been in touch with the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> and will want to develop a relationship with them,'' Coors said. The transaction is subject to the negotiation of a definitive agreement, approval by the boards of directors of both companies, and review by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATI