<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is asking <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> to disclose how much foreign influence over the airline a planned employee-management takeover would allow, officials said. The inquiry came as The Wall Street Journal reported that <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> had asked <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' new principle owner, <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON>, to cut by $ 225 million the $ 400 million investment made in <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the airline's parent corporation, by <ORGANIZATION> KLM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Monday gave <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> parent <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, until Oct. 10 to furnish information on investors and financial arrangements in the $ 6.5 billion stock buyout plan of <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> by the airline's pilots, management and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> is to continue as head of the company under the plan, which would give controlling interest to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> employees. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shane </PERSON>, assistant transportation secretary for policy and international affairs, asked <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON> to provide detailed financial information, including the names of any foreign investors and the amount of influence they might have over the new company. The department is conducting a financial fitness review of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> deal to determine whether it will extend the airline's operating certificate under the new ownership A similar review of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> takeover was completed last week but the results were not announced to the public. `` We are concerned about any aquisition,'' <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> said in the letter to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, `` especially a leverage buyout of either the carrier or its parent that could have a substantial adverse impact on a carrier's financial structure, might otherwise affect its ability to operate safely or meet its financial obligations, or would result in its not being controlled by <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. citizens.'' On the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> takeover, department spokesman <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Paris </PERSON> said he could not confirm the Journal report or give any details of the department's decision on the buyout. <ORGANIZATION> KLM </ORGANIZATION> made its investment in <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> to help <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> finance the $ 3.65 billion purchase. <ORGANIZATION> KLM </ORGANIZATION> provided 57 percent of the $ 700 million in equity <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> raised to buy <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> but owns only 5 percent of the airline. Foreign companies can not own more than 25 percent of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airline, but <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said last week he was concerned that foreign investors might have more influence than their ownership reflects and could compromise <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiations with other governments over air routes. The Journal also reported that rumors about possible changes in <ORGANIZATION> KLM </ORGANIZATION>'s Northwest investment sparked a sell-off of stock in <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' parent corporation. <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> plans to invest $ 750 million in <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>. The department, in its letter to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, asked for a `` citizenship affidavit'' for <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> as it will exist after the takeover. `` Detail any actual or potential ability on the part of these non-citizen entities to influence or control, directly or indirectly, the affairs of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> instructed in the letter. He also asked for any written or oral agreements that might assure that non-citizen lenders can not control <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>.
